{"title_page": "Henschel Hs 129", "text_new": "{{short description|German twin engine WWII ground attack aircraft}}\n{{More footnotes|date=August 2010}}\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n  |name = Hs 129\n  |image = Henschel Hs 129B.jpg\n  |caption = A captured Henschel Hs 129 B-1 at [[Freeman Army Airfield]], Indiana, 1946\n}}{{Infobox aircraft type\n  |type = Ground-attack\n  |manufacturer = [[Henschel]]\n  |designer = <!--only appropriate for single designers, not project leaders-->\n  |first flight = 25 May 1939\n  |introduced = April 1942\n  |retired = 1945\n  |status = <!--in most cases, this field is redundant; use it sparingly-->\n  |primary user = ''[[Luftwaffe]]''\n  |more users = [[Hungarian Air Force]]<br/>[[Romanian Air Force]]\n  |produced = June 1940 \u2013 September 1944\n  |number built = 865\n  |unit cost =\n  |developed from = <!-- the aircraft which formed the basis for the topic type -->\n  |variants with their own articles = <!-- variants OF the topic type -->}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Henschel Hs 129''' was a [[World War II]] [[ground-attack aircraft]] fielded by the [[Germany|German]] ''[[Luftwaffe]]''. The aircraft saw combat in [[Battle of Tunisia|Tunisia]] and on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]].\n\nA key requirement of the original specification was that the aircraft be powered by engines that were not in demand for other designs. Prototypes with low-power german [[Argus As 410]] engines of {{cvt|465|PS|hp kW|0}} failed acceptance test, a more powerful replacement was found with the french [[Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 14M]] engine of {{cvt|700|PS|hp kW|0}}. \n\nThe design was relatively effective when it was first introduced, and saw service on the Eastern Front in a variety of front-line roles. As the war continued and anti-tank support became the main goal, the aircraft was continually up-gunned, eventually mounting a 75&nbsp;mm gun in the anti-tank role that left the plane barely flyable. Only a small number of these B-3 models were produced, late in the war.\n\n==Design and development==\nBy the mid-1930s, the German military, as well as its counterparts in other countries, had come to see the main role of ground-attack aircraft as the [[interdiction]] of logistics and [[materiel]], a task in which targets were often poorly protected and less likely to be defended by strong, well-coordinated defences. For high-value, well-protected tactical targets, the [[dive bomber]] was becoming the conventional solution.\n\nThe experience of the German ''[[Condor Legion|Kondor Legion]]'' during the [[Spanish Civil War]] (1936&ndash;39) refuted this idea. Even though it was equipped with types unsuited to the role, such as the [[Henschel Hs 123]] and [[Autocannon|cannon]]-armed versions of the [[Heinkel He 112]], the ''Kondor Legion'' proved that ground-attack aircraft were a very effective weapon. This led to support within the ''Luftwaffe'' for the creation of an aircraft dedicated to this role, and the [[Ministry of Aviation (Germany)|''Reichsluftministerium'']] (RLM; \"[[Reich]] Air Ministry\") requested tenders for a specialized ground attack aircraft.\n\nIt was anticipated that the main source of damage to such an aircraft would be [[small arms]] fire from the ground, meaning that the plane had to be well-[[Vehicle armour|armored]] around its [[cockpit]] and engines. Similar protection was also needed in the [[canopy (aircraft)|canopy]], in the form of 75&nbsp;mm (2.95&nbsp;in) thick [[Bullet-proof glass|armored glass]]. The aircraft was expected to be attacking in low-level, head-on [[strafing]] runs, so the cockpit had to be located as close as possible to the nose, in order to maximize the visibility of its targets. Another, non-operational, requirement severely hampered the designs: the RLM insisted that the new design be powered by engines that were not being used in existing aircraft, so that the type would not interfere with the production of established types deemed essential to the war effort.\n\nOnly four companies were asked to submit tenders; three submissions followed and only two of these were considered worthy of consideration: One derived from an existing [[Focke-Wulf Flugzeugbau GmbH|Focke-Wulf]] reconnaissance type, the [[Focke-Wulf Fw 189|Fw 189]], the other was Henschel's all-new Hs 129.\n\n===Prototypes===\nThe Hs 129 was designed around a single large \"bathtub\" of steel sheeting that made up the entire nose area of the plane, completely enclosing the [[Aviator|pilot]] up to head level. Even the canopy was steel, with only tiny windows on the side to see out of and two angled blocks of glass for the windscreen. In order to improve the armor's ability to deflect bullets, the [[fuselage]] sides were angled in forming a triangular shape, resulting in almost no room to move at shoulder level. There was so little room in the cockpit that the instrument panel ended up under the nose below the windscreen where it was almost invisible; some of the engine instruments were moved outside onto the engine nacelles' inboard-facing surfaces and the gunsight was mounted outside on the nose.\n\nHenschel's plane came in 12 percent overweight with the engines 8 percent underpowered, and understandably, it flew poorly. The [[Aircraft flight control system|controls]] proved to be almost inoperable as speed increased, and in testing, the V2 prototype flew into the ground from a short dive on 5 January 1940<ref>http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/weapons_henschel_hs_129.html</ref> because the stick forces were too high for the pilot to pull out. The Focke-Wulf  design proved to be no better. Both planes were underpowered with their air-cooled, inverted-V12 [[Argus As 410]] engines, and very difficult to fly.\n\nThe RLM nevertheless felt they should continue with the basic concept. The only real deciding factor between the two designs was that the Henschel was smaller and cheaper. The Focke-Wulf was put on low priority as a backup, and testing continued with the Hs 129 A-0. A series of improvements resulted in the '''Hs 129 A-1''' series, armed with two 20&nbsp;mm [[MG 151 cannon|MG 151/20 cannon]]s and two 7.92&nbsp;mm (.312&nbsp;in) [[MG 17 machine gun]]s, along with the ability to carry four 50&nbsp;kg (110&nbsp;lb) bombs under the fuselage centreline.\n\n===Hs 129 B-1===\nEven before the A-1s were delivered, the plane was redesigned with [[Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 14M]] [[radial engine]]s, which were captured in some number when [[Battle of France|France fell]] and continued to be produced under German occupation. This engine supplied {{cvt|700|PS|hp kW|0}} for takeoff, compared to the Argus at {{cvt|465|PS|hp kW|0}}. The Gnome-Rhone radials were also made in versions with [[Counter-rotating propellers|opposite rotation for the propeller]], and were installed on the Hs 129 with the port engine rotating clockwise and the starboard rotating counterclockwise, as seen from nose-on, thus eliminating engine [[torque]] problems.\n\nThe A-1 planes were converted into '''Hs 129 B-0'''s for testing (although it has been claimed that some As were sold to [[Romania]]) and the pilots were reportedly much happier with the results. Their main complaint was the view from the canopy, so a single larger windscreen and a new canopy with much better vision were added, resulting in the production model '''Hs 129 B-1'''.\n\nB-1s started rolling off the lines in December 1941, but they were delivered at a trickle. In preparation for the new plane, I./[[Schlachtgeschwader 1|SchlG 1]] had been formed up in January with [[Messerschmitt Bf 109 variants#Bf 109E \"Emil\"|Bf 109 E/Bs]] (fighter-bomber version of Bf 109 E) and [[Henschel Hs 123|Hs 123]]s, and they delivered B-0s and every B-1 that was completed. Still, it was not until April that 12 B-1s were delivered and the 4th ''staffel'' (squadron) became ready for action. They moved to the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]] (to [[Crimea]]) in the middle of May 1942, and in June they received a new weapon, the 30&nbsp;mm (1.2&nbsp;in) [[MK 101 cannon]] with armor-piercing ammunition in a centerline [[Gun pod|pod]].\n\n===Hs 129 B-2===\nDeliveries of the new '''Hs 129 B-2''' model began in May 1942, side by side with the B-1 (of which just 50 planes had been delivered at that point). The only difference between the two were changes to the fuel system &ndash; a host of other minor changes could be found almost at random on either model. These changes accumulated in the B-2 production line until they could eventually be told apart at a glance; the main differences being the removal of the mast for the radio antenna, the addition of a [[Radio direction finder|direction-finding]] [[Antenna (radio)|radio antenna]] loop, and shorter exhaust stacks on the engines.\n\nIn the field, the differences seemed to be more pronounced. The ''[[R\u00fcstsatz]]'' field refit kits were renumbered and some were dropped, and in general, the B-2 planes received the upgraded cannon pack using a 30&nbsp;mm [[MK 103 cannon]] instead of the earlier MK 101. These guns both fired the same ammunition, but the 103 did so at almost twice the rate.\n\nBy late 1942 reports were coming in about the ineffectiveness of the MK 101 against newer versions of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[T-34]] [[tank]]s. One obvious solution would be to use the larger {{convert|3.7|cm|in|abbr=on|2}} [[BK 3,7]] (''Bordkanone'' 3,7), recently adapted from the ground-based [[3.7 cm FlaK 43|Flak 18]]. These guns had already been converted into underwing pod-mounted weapons for the [[Junkers Ju 87G]] and found to be an effective weapon, despite the fact that only 12 shells per pod could be accommodated. When mounted on the Hs 129, the empty area behind the cockpit could be used for ammunition storage, greatly increasing the supply compared to the Ju. The B-2/R3 package introduced the [[BK 3,7]] {{convert|3.7|cm|in|abbr=on|2}} automatic cannon, but relatively few aircraft were converted in favour of the B-3, mounting the BK 7,5.\n\n===Hs 129 B-3===\n[[File:Hs 129B-3.jpg|thumb|right|A closeup of the ''Bordkanone'' BK 7,5 75 mm cannon.]]\n\nIt was decided that the {{convert|7.5|cm|in|abbr=on|2}} semi-automatic [[Rheinmetall]] [[7.5 cm Pak 40|PaK 40]] anti-tank gun, which had already been adapted for use in the [[Junkers Ju 88]]P-1, would be further modified for use in the Hs 129. This resulted in the BK 7,5 (''Bordkanone'' 7,5), which, even though it weighed {{convert|1200|kg|abbr=on}}, was lighter than the PaK 40. Fully automatic, it featured a new, [[Hydraulics|hydraulic]] [[recoil]]-dampening system and a new, more aerodynamic [[muzzle brake]]. An [[autoloader]] system, with 12 rounds in a rotary magazine, was fitted in the empty space behind the cockpit, within the rear half of the wing root area. The gun and its recoil mechanism occupied a substantial [[gun pod]] under the fuselage, and a circular port at the rear of the pod allowed rearwards ejection of spent cartridges immediately after firing. While this new variant, the '''Hs 129 B-3''', was theoretically capable of destroying any tank in the world, the added weight worsened the aircraft's general performance and it was inferior to previous variants.<ref>[http://www.deutscheluftwaffe.de/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/b/Bordwaffen/Bordkanonen/BordkanoneBK75/bordkanone75.html DeutscheLuftwaffe.de's German language page for the BK 7,5 autocannon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517081256/http://www.deutscheluftwaffe.de/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/b/Bordwaffen/Bordkanonen/BordkanoneBK75/bordkanone75.html |date=2016-05-17 }}</ref>\n\nThe ''Bordkanone'' 7,5 was the heaviest and most powerful forward-firing weapon fitted to a production [[military aircraft]] during World War II. The only other aircraft to be factory-equipped with similar-calibre guns were the 1,420 examples of the North American [[B-25 Mitchell#Variants|B-25G and B-25H Mitchell]], which mounted either a {{convert|75|mm|in|abbr=on|2}} [[75 mm Gun M2/M3/M6|M4 cannon]], or lightweight T13E1 or M5 versions of the same gun.\n\nFrom June 1944, only 25 examples of the Hs 129 B-3 arrived at frontline units before the production line was shut down in September (a small number were reportedly also created by converting B-2 aircraft). In the field the B-3 proved effective, but its small numbers had little effect on the war effort.\n\n===Hs 129 C===\nIn order to address the poor performance of the aircraft, plans had been under way for some time to fit the plane with newer versions of the [[Italy|Italian]] [[Isotta-Fraschini Delta]] air-cooled inverted V12 inline engine that delivered 630&nbsp;kW (850&nbsp;hp) and weighed some 510 kg (1,111 lb) apiece, providing more power than Germany's own [[Argus As 411]] engine of similar configuration and lighter (385 kg) weight. The engine installation ran into a number of delays however, and was still not ready for production when the plant was overrun by the Allies in 1945.\n\n===Hs 129 D===\nPlanned version of the Hs 129. Powered by either two 1085&nbsp;hp [[Junkers Jumo 211]] or two 1539&nbsp;hp [[BMW 801]] to improve its performance. No prototypes were made.\n\n==Operators==\n;{{flag|Nazi Germany|name='''Germany'''}}\n*''[[Luftwaffe]]''\n;{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u201346)}}\n*[[Royal Hungarian Air Force]]\n;{{flag|Kingdom of Romania|name=Romania}}\n*[[Royal Romanian Air Force]]\n\n==Specifications (Hs 129B-2)==\n[[File:Henschel hs-129B.svg|right|300px]]\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=Henschel Hs 129...der gefl\u00fcgelte B\u00fcchsen\u00f6ffner<ref name=\"AI dec80 p281\">''Air International'' December 1980, p. 281.</ref>\n|prime units?=met\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|crew=1\n|length m=9.75\n|span m=14.2\n|height m=3.25\n|wing area sqm=29\n|aspect ratio=<!-- sailplanes -->\n|airfoil=\n|empty weight kg=4020\n|gross weight kg=\n|max takeoff weight kg=5250\n|fuel capacity=\n|more general=\n<!--\n        Powerplant\n-->\n|eng1 number=2\n|eng1 name=[[Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 14M|Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 14M-4/-5]]\n|eng1 type=14-cylinder air-cooled radial engine\n|eng1 kw=515\n|power original=700 PS\n|eng1 note=<ref>https://www.deutscheluftwaffe.com/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/h/Henschel/Hs%20192/Hs_129_B_0%20Handbuch.pdf</ref> for take-off\n|prop blade number=3\n|prop name=Ratier constant speed propeller\n|prop dia m=2.6\n|prop dia ft=8\n|prop dia in=6\n|prop dia note=<ref>https://www.deutscheluftwaffe.com/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/h/Henschel/Hs%20192/Hs_129_B_0%20Handbuch.pdf</ref>\n|max speed kmh=407\n|max speed note=at {{cvt|3830|m}}\n|cruise speed kmh=315\n|cruise speed note=at {{cvt|3000|m}}\n|stall speed kmh=\n|stall speed mph=\n|stall speed kts=\n|stall speed note=\n|minimum control speed kmh=\n|minimum control speed mph=\n|minimum control speed kts=\n|minimum control speed note=\n|range km=690\n|combat range km=\n|combat range miles=\n|combat range nmi=\n|combat range note=\n|ferry range km=\n|ferry range miles=\n|ferry range nmi=\n|ferry range note=\n|endurance=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|ceiling m=9000\n|g limits=<!-- aerobatic -->\n|roll rate=<!-- aerobatic -->\n|climb rate ms=8.1\n|time to altitude=\n|wing loading kg/m2=\n|fuel consumption kg/km=\n|fuel consumption lb/mi=\n|power/mass=\n|more performance=\n<!--\n        Armament\n-->\n|guns=<br/>\n** 2 x 7.92 mm (0.31 in) [[MG 17 machine gun]]s, later models from 1943 to 1944 replaced the MG 17s with 2 x 13 mm (.51 in) [[MG 131 machine gun]]s\n** 2 x 20 mm [[MG 151/20 cannon]] ''or''\n** a {{cvt|30|mm|3}} [[MK 101 cannon]] or [[MK 103 cannon]] in a conformally mounted gun pod (B-2/R-2).\n|bombs=<br/>\n**2 x {{cvt|50|kg}} bombs on underwing hardpoints\n**4 x {{cvt|50|kg}} fragmentation bombs on belly racks\n|rockets= \n|missiles=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent|\n|related=\n|similar aircraft=\n*[[Ilyushin Il-2]]\n*[[Junkers Ju 87|Junkers Ju 87D/G]]\n*[[Tomashevich Pegas]]\n|lists=\n* [[List of aircraft of World War II]]\n*[[List of military aircraft of Germany]]\n|see also=\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deutscheluftwaffe.com/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/h/Henschel/Hs%20192/Hs_129_B_0%20Handbuch.pdf|title=Hs 129 B-0 Fkugzeug-Handbuch|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n===Bibliography===\n* Bern\u00e1d, D\u00e9nes. ''Henschel Hs 129 in Action (Aircraft Number 176)''. Carrollton, TX: Squadron/Signal Publications, Inc., 2001. {{ISBN|0-89747-428-7}}.\n* Bern\u00e1d, D\u00e9nes. ''Henschel Hs 129 (Military Aircraft in Detail)''. Hinckley, UK: Midland publishing Ltd., 2006. {{ISBN|1-85780-238-1}}.\n* Chor\u0105\u017cykiewicz, Przemys\u0142aw. ''Henschel Hs 129''. Sandomierz, Poland/Redbourn, UK: Mushroom Model Publications, 2008. {{ISBN|9788389450463}}.\n* Green, William. ''Warplanes of the Third Reich''. London: Macdonald and Jane's Publishers Ltd., 1970 (fourth impression 1979). {{ISBN|0-356-02382-6}}.\n* \"Henschel Hs 129...der gefl\u00fcgelte B\u00fcchsen\u00f6ffner\". ''[[Air International]]'', December 1980, Vol 19 No 6. pp.&nbsp;277\u2013283, 303\u2013304. {{ISSN|0306-5634}}.\n* Kempski, Benedykt. ''Samolot szturmowy Henschel Hs 129 (Typy Broni i Uzbrojenia No.214)'' (in Polish). Warszawa, Poland: 2004. {{ISBN|83-11-10010-1}}.\n* Pegg, Martin; Creek, Eddie; Tullis, Thomas A. and Bentley: ''Hs 129: Panzerj\u00e4ger! (Classic series, No. 2)'' West Sussex, UK: Classic Publications, 1997. {{ISBN|0-9526867-1-6}}.\n* Smith, J.Richard. ''The Henschel Hs 129 (Aircraft in Profile No.69)''. Leatherhead, Surrey, UK: Profile Publications Ltd., 1966.\n* Smith, J.Richard and Kay, Anthony. ''German Aircraft of the Second World War''. London: Putnam & Company Ltd., 1972 (third impression 1978). {{ISBN|0-370-00024-2}}.\n* Stachura, Petr; Bern\u00e1d, D\u00e9nes and Haladej, Dan. ''Henschel Hs 129'' (in Czech). Prague, Czech Republic: MBI, 1993 (second edition 1996 bilingual Czech/English). {{ISBN|80-901263-4-0}}.\n* Wood, Tony and Gunston, Bill. ''Hitler's Luftwaffe: A pictorial history and technical encyclopedia of Hitler's air power in World War II''. London: Salamander Books Ltd., 1977. {{ISBN|0-86101-005-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Henschel Hs 129}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160317053118/http://www.deutscheluftwaffe.de/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/h/Henschel/Hs%20192/Hs%20129%20B3%20-%207.5%20BK.pdf German WW II manual for Hs 129B-3's ''Bordkanone'' BK 7,5 cannon installation]\n\n{{Henschel aircraft}}\n{{RLM aircraft designations}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1930s German attack aircraft]]\n[[Category:Henschel aircraft|129]]\n[[Category:World War II ground attack aircraft of Germany]]\n[[Category:Low-wing aircraft]]\n[[Category:Aircraft first flown in 1939]]\n[[Category:Twin piston-engined tractor aircraft]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German twin engine WWII ground attack aircraft}}\n{{More footnotes|date=August 2010}}\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n  |name = Hs 129\n  |image = Henschel Hs 129B.jpg\n  |caption = A captured Henschel Hs 129 B-1 at [[Freeman Army Airfield]], Indiana, 1946\n}}{{Infobox aircraft type\n  |type = Ground-attack\n  |manufacturer = [[Henschel]]\n  |designer = <!--only appropriate for single designers, not project leaders-->\n  |first flight = 25 May 1939\n  |introduced = April 1942\n  |retired = 1945\n  |status = <!--in most cases, this field is redundant; use it sparingly-->\n  |primary user = ''[[Luftwaffe]]''\n  |more users = [[Hungarian Air Force]]<br/>[[Romanian Air Force]]\n  |produced = June 1940 \u2013 September 1944\n  |number built = 865\n  |unit cost =\n  |developed from = <!-- the aircraft which formed the basis for the topic type -->\n  |variants with their own articles = <!-- variants OF the topic type -->}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Henschel Hs 129''' was a [[World War II]] [[ground-attack aircraft]] fielded by the [[Germany|German]] ''[[Luftwaffe]]''. The aircraft saw combat in [[Battle of Tunisia|Tunisia]] and on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]].\n\nA key requirement of the original specification was that the aircraft be powered by engines that were not in demand for other designs. Prototypes with low-power german [[Argus As 410]] engines of {{cvt|465|PS|hp kW|0}} failed acceptance test, a more powerful replacement was found with the french [[Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 14M]] engine of {{cvt|700|PS|hp kW|0}}. \n\nThe design was relatively effective when it was first introduced, and saw service on the Eastern Front in a variety of front-line roles. As the war continued and anti-tank support became the main goal, the aircraft was continually up-gunned, eventually mounting a 75&nbsp;mm gun in the anti-tank role that left the plane barely flyable. Only a small number of these B-3 models were produced, late in the war.\n\n==Design and development==\nBy the mid-1930s, the German military, as well as its counterparts in other countries, had come to see the main role of ground-attack aircraft as the [[interdiction]] of logistics and [[materiel]], a task in which targets were often poorly protected and less likely to be defended by strong, well-coordinated defences. For high-value, well-protected tactical targets, the [[dive bomber]] was becoming the conventional solution.\n\nThe experience of the German ''[[Condor Legion|Kondor Legion]]'' during the [[Spanish Civil War]] (1936&ndash;39) refuted this idea. Even though it was equipped with types unsuited to the role, such as the [[Henschel Hs 123]] and [[Autocannon|cannon]]-armed versions of the [[Heinkel He 112]], the ''Kondor Legion'' proved that ground-attack aircraft were a very effective weapon. This led to support within the ''Luftwaffe'' for the creation of an aircraft dedicated to this role, and the [[Ministry of Aviation (Germany)|''Reichsluftministerium'']] (RLM; \"[[Reich]] Air Ministry\") requested tenders for a specialized ground attack aircraft.\n\nIt was anticipated that the main source of damage to such an aircraft would be [[small arms]] fire from the ground, meaning that the plane had to be well-[[Vehicle armour|armored]] around its [[cockpit]] and engines. Similar protection was also needed in the [[canopy (aircraft)|canopy]], in the form of 75&nbsp;mm (2.95&nbsp;in) thick [[Bullet-proof glass|armored glass]]. The aircraft was expected to be attacking in low-level, head-on [[strafing]] runs, so the cockpit had to be located as close as possible to the nose, in order to maximize the visibility of its targets. Another, non-operational, requirement severely hampered the designs: the RLM insisted that the new design be powered by engines that were not being used in existing aircraft, so that the type would not interfere with the production of established types deemed essential to the war effort.\n\nOnly four companies were asked to submit tenders; three submissions followed and only two of these were considered worthy of consideration: One derived from an existing [[Focke-Wulf Flugzeugbau GmbH|Focke-Wulf]] reconnaissance type, the [[Focke-Wulf Fw 189|Fw 189]], the other was Henschel's all-new Hs 129.\n\n===Prototypes===\nThe Hs 129 was designed around a single large \"bathtub\" of steel sheeting that made up the entire nose area of the plane, completely enclosing the [[Aviator|pilot]] up to head level. Even the canopy was steel, with only tiny windows on the side to see out of and two angled blocks of glass for the windscreen. In order to improve the armor's ability to deflect bullets, the [[fuselage]] sides were angled in forming a triangular shape, resulting in almost no room to move at shoulder level. There was so little room in the cockpit that the instrument panel ended up under the nose below the windscreen where it was almost invisible; some of the engine instruments were moved outside onto the engine nacelles' inboard-facing surfaces and the gunsight was mounted outside on the nose.\n\nHenschel's plane came in 12 percent overweight with the engines 8 percent underpowered, and understandably, it flew poorly. The [[Aircraft flight control system|controls]] proved to be almost inoperable as speed increased, and in testing, the V2 prototype flew into the ground from a short dive on 5 January 1940<ref>http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/weapons_henschel_hs_129.html</ref> because the stick forces were too high for the pilot to pull out. The Focke-Wulf  design proved to be no better. Both planes were underpowered with their air-cooled, inverted-V12 [[Argus As 410]] engines, and very difficult to fly.\n\nThe RLM nevertheless felt they should continue with the basic concept. The only real deciding factor between the two designs was that the Henschel was smaller and cheaper. The Focke-Wulf was put on low priority as a backup, and testing continued with the Hs 129 A-0. A series of improvements resulted in the '''Hs 129 A-1''' series, armed with two 20&nbsp;mm [[MG 151 cannon|MG 151/20 cannon]]s and two 7.92&nbsp;mm (.312&nbsp;in) [[MG 17 machine gun]]s, along with the ability to carry four 50&nbsp;kg (110&nbsp;lb) bombs under the fuselage centreline.\n\n===Hs 129 B-1===\nEven before the A-1s were delivered, the plane was redesigned with [[Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 14M]] [[radial engine]]s, which were captured in some number when [[Battle of France|France fell]] and continued to be produced under German occupation. This engine supplied {{cvt|700|PS|hp kW|0}} for takeoff, compared to the Argus at {{cvt|465|PS|hp kW|0}}. The Gnome-Rhone radials were also made in versions with [[Counter-rotating propellers|opposite rotation for the propeller]], and were installed on the Hs 129 with the port engine rotating clockwise and the starboard rotating counterclockwise, as seen from nose-on, thus eliminating engine [[torque]] problems.\n\nThe A-1 planes were converted into '''Hs 129 B-0'''s for testing (although it has been claimed that some As were sold to [[Romania]]) and the pilots were reportedly much happier with the results. Their main complaint was the view from the canopy, so a single larger windscreen and a new canopy with much better vision were added, resulting in the production model '''Hs 129 B-1'''.\n\nB-1s started rolling off the lines in December 1941, but they were delivered at a trickle. In preparation for the new plane, I./[[Schlachtgeschwader 1|SchlG 1]] had been formed up in January with [[Messerschmitt Bf 109 variants#Bf 109E \"Emil\"|Bf 109 E/Bs]] (fighter-bomber version of Bf 109 E) and [[Henschel Hs 123|Hs 123]]s, and they delivered B-0s and every B-1 that was completed. Still, it was not until April that 12 B-1s were delivered and the 4th ''staffel'' (squadron) became ready for action. They moved to the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]] (to [[Crimea]]) in the middle of May 1942, and in June they received a new weapon, the 30&nbsp;mm (1.2&nbsp;in) [[MK 101 cannon]] with armor-piercing ammunition in a centerline [[Gun pod|pod]].\n\n===Hs 129 B-2===\nDeliveries of the new '''Hs 129 B-2''' model began in May 1942, side by side with the B-1 (of which just 50 planes had been delivered at that point). The only difference between the two were changes to the fuel system &ndash; a host of other minor changes could be found almost at random on either model. These changes accumulated in the B-2 production line until they could eventually be told apart at a glance; the main differences being the removal of the mast for the radio antenna, the addition of a [[Radio direction finder|direction-finding]] [[Antenna (radio)|radio antenna]] loop, and shorter exhaust stacks on the engines.\n\nIn the field, the differences seemed to be more pronounced. The ''[[R\u00fcstsatz]]'' field refit kits were renumbered and some were dropped, and in general, the B-2 planes received the upgraded cannon pack using a 30&nbsp;mm [[MK 103 cannon]] instead of the earlier MK 101. These guns both fired the same ammunition, but the 103 did so at almost twice the rate.\n\nBy late 1942 reports were coming in about the ineffectiveness of the MK 101 against newer versions of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[T-34]] [[tank]]s. One obvious solution would be to use the larger {{convert|3.7|cm|in|abbr=on|2}} [[BK 3,7]] (''Bordkanone'' 3,7), recently adapted from the ground-based [[3.7 cm FlaK 43|Flak 18]]. These guns had already been converted into underwing pod-mounted weapons for the [[Junkers Ju 87G]] and found to be an effective weapon, despite the fact that only 12 shells per pod could be accommodated. When mounted on the Hs 129, the empty area behind the cockpit could be used for ammunition storage, which would address the only problem with the Ju 87's mounting: the limited ammunition supply. The B-2/R3 package introduced the [[BK 3,7]] {{convert|3.7|cm|in|abbr=on|2}} automatic cannon, but relatively few aircraft were converted in favour of the B-3, mounting the BK 7,5.\n\n===Hs 129 B-3===\n[[File:Hs 129B-3.jpg|thumb|right|A closeup of the ''Bordkanone'' BK 7,5 75 mm cannon.]]\n\nIt was decided that the {{convert|7.5|cm|in|abbr=on|2}} semi-automatic [[Rheinmetall]] [[7.5 cm Pak 40|PaK 40]] anti-tank gun, which had already been adapted for use in the [[Junkers Ju 88]]P-1, would be further modified for use in the Hs 129. This resulted in the BK 7,5 (''Bordkanone'' 7,5), which, even though it weighed {{convert|1200|kg|abbr=on}}, was lighter than the PaK 40. Fully automatic, it featured a new, [[Hydraulics|hydraulic]] [[recoil]]-dampening system and a new, more aerodynamic [[muzzle brake]]. An [[autoloader]] system, with 12 rounds in a rotary magazine, was fitted in the empty space behind the cockpit, within the rear half of the wing root area. The gun and its recoil mechanism occupied a substantial [[gun pod]] under the fuselage, and a circular port at the rear of the pod allowed rearwards ejection of spent cartridges immediately after firing. While this new variant, the '''Hs 129 B-3''', was theoretically capable of destroying any tank in the world, the added weight worsened the aircraft's general performance and it was inferior to previous variants.<ref>[http://www.deutscheluftwaffe.de/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/b/Bordwaffen/Bordkanonen/BordkanoneBK75/bordkanone75.html DeutscheLuftwaffe.de's German language page for the BK 7,5 autocannon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517081256/http://www.deutscheluftwaffe.de/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/b/Bordwaffen/Bordkanonen/BordkanoneBK75/bordkanone75.html |date=2016-05-17 }}</ref>\n\nThe ''Bordkanone'' 7,5 was the heaviest and most powerful forward-firing weapon fitted to a production [[military aircraft]] during World War II. The only other aircraft to be factory-equipped with similar-calibre guns were the 1,420 examples of the North American [[B-25 Mitchell#Variants|B-25G and B-25H Mitchell]], which mounted either a {{convert|75|mm|in|abbr=on|2}} [[75 mm Gun M2/M3/M6|M4 cannon]], or lightweight T13E1 or M5 versions of the same gun.\n\nFrom June 1944, only 25 examples of the Hs 129 B-3 arrived at frontline units before the production line was shut down in September (a small number were reportedly also created by converting B-2 aircraft). In the field the B-3 proved effective, but its small numbers had little effect on the war effort.\n\n===Hs 129 C===\nIn order to address the poor performance of the aircraft, plans had been under way for some time to fit the plane with newer versions of the [[Italy|Italian]] [[Isotta-Fraschini Delta]] air-cooled inverted V12 inline engine that delivered 630&nbsp;kW (850&nbsp;hp) and weighed some 510 kg (1,111 lb) apiece, providing more power than Germany's own [[Argus As 411]] engine of similar configuration and lighter (385 kg) weight. The engine installation ran into a number of delays however, and was still not ready for production when the plant was overrun by the Allies in 1945.\n\n===Hs 129 D===\nPlanned version of the Hs 129. Powered by either two 1085&nbsp;hp [[Junkers Jumo 211]] or two 1539&nbsp;hp [[BMW 801]] to improve its performance. No prototypes were made.\n\n==Operators==\n;{{flag|Nazi Germany|name='''Germany'''}}\n*''[[Luftwaffe]]''\n;{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u201346)}}\n*[[Royal Hungarian Air Force]]\n;{{flag|Kingdom of Romania|name=Romania}}\n*[[Royal Romanian Air Force]]\n\n==Specifications (Hs 129B-2)==\n[[File:Henschel hs-129B.svg|right|300px]]\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=Henschel Hs 129...der gefl\u00fcgelte B\u00fcchsen\u00f6ffner<ref name=\"AI dec80 p281\">''Air International'' December 1980, p. 281.</ref>\n|prime units?=met\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|crew=1\n|length m=9.75\n|span m=14.2\n|height m=3.25\n|wing area sqm=29\n|aspect ratio=<!-- sailplanes -->\n|airfoil=\n|empty weight kg=4020\n|gross weight kg=\n|max takeoff weight kg=5250\n|fuel capacity=\n|more general=\n<!--\n        Powerplant\n-->\n|eng1 number=2\n|eng1 name=[[Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 14M|Gnome-Rh\u00f4ne 14M-4/-5]]\n|eng1 type=14-cylinder air-cooled radial engine\n|eng1 kw=515\n|power original=700 PS\n|eng1 note=<ref>https://www.deutscheluftwaffe.com/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/h/Henschel/Hs%20192/Hs_129_B_0%20Handbuch.pdf</ref> for take-off\n|prop blade number=3\n|prop name=Ratier constant speed propeller\n|prop dia m=2.6\n|prop dia ft=8\n|prop dia in=6\n|prop dia note=<ref>https://www.deutscheluftwaffe.com/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/h/Henschel/Hs%20192/Hs_129_B_0%20Handbuch.pdf</ref>\n|max speed kmh=407\n|max speed note=at {{cvt|3830|m}}\n|cruise speed kmh=315\n|cruise speed note=at {{cvt|3000|m}}\n|stall speed kmh=\n|stall speed mph=\n|stall speed kts=\n|stall speed note=\n|minimum control speed kmh=\n|minimum control speed mph=\n|minimum control speed kts=\n|minimum control speed note=\n|range km=690\n|combat range km=\n|combat range miles=\n|combat range nmi=\n|combat range note=\n|ferry range km=\n|ferry range miles=\n|ferry range nmi=\n|ferry range note=\n|endurance=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|ceiling m=9000\n|g limits=<!-- aerobatic -->\n|roll rate=<!-- aerobatic -->\n|climb rate ms=8.1\n|time to altitude=\n|wing loading kg/m2=\n|fuel consumption kg/km=\n|fuel consumption lb/mi=\n|power/mass=\n|more performance=\n<!--\n        Armament\n-->\n|guns=<br/>\n** 2 x 7.92 mm (0.31 in) [[MG 17 machine gun]]s, later models from 1943 to 1944 replaced the MG 17s with 2 x 13 mm (.51 in) [[MG 131 machine gun]]s\n** 2 x 20 mm [[MG 151/20 cannon]] ''or''\n** a {{cvt|30|mm|3}} [[MK 101 cannon]] or [[MK 103 cannon]] in a conformally mounted gun pod (B-2/R-2).\n|bombs=<br/>\n**2 x {{cvt|50|kg}} bombs on underwing hardpoints\n**4 x {{cvt|50|kg}} fragmentation bombs on belly racks\n|rockets= \n|missiles=\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent|\n|related=\n|similar aircraft=\n*[[Ilyushin Il-2]]\n*[[Junkers Ju 87|Junkers Ju 87D/G]]\n*[[Tomashevich Pegas]]\n|lists=\n* [[List of aircraft of World War II]]\n*[[List of military aircraft of Germany]]\n|see also=\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deutscheluftwaffe.com/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/h/Henschel/Hs%20192/Hs_129_B_0%20Handbuch.pdf|title=Hs 129 B-0 Fkugzeug-Handbuch|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n===Bibliography===\n* Bern\u00e1d, D\u00e9nes. ''Henschel Hs 129 in Action (Aircraft Number 176)''. Carrollton, TX: Squadron/Signal Publications, Inc., 2001. {{ISBN|0-89747-428-7}}.\n* Bern\u00e1d, D\u00e9nes. ''Henschel Hs 129 (Military Aircraft in Detail)''. Hinckley, UK: Midland publishing Ltd., 2006. {{ISBN|1-85780-238-1}}.\n* Chor\u0105\u017cykiewicz, Przemys\u0142aw. ''Henschel Hs 129''. Sandomierz, Poland/Redbourn, UK: Mushroom Model Publications, 2008. {{ISBN|9788389450463}}.\n* Green, William. ''Warplanes of the Third Reich''. London: Macdonald and Jane's Publishers Ltd., 1970 (fourth impression 1979). {{ISBN|0-356-02382-6}}.\n* \"Henschel Hs 129...der gefl\u00fcgelte B\u00fcchsen\u00f6ffner\". ''[[Air International]]'', December 1980, Vol 19 No 6. pp.&nbsp;277\u2013283, 303\u2013304. {{ISSN|0306-5634}}.\n* Kempski, Benedykt. ''Samolot szturmowy Henschel Hs 129 (Typy Broni i Uzbrojenia No.214)'' (in Polish). Warszawa, Poland: 2004. {{ISBN|83-11-10010-1}}.\n* Pegg, Martin; Creek, Eddie; Tullis, Thomas A. and Bentley: ''Hs 129: Panzerj\u00e4ger! (Classic series, No. 2)'' West Sussex, UK: Classic Publications, 1997. {{ISBN|0-9526867-1-6}}.\n* Smith, J.Richard. ''The Henschel Hs 129 (Aircraft in Profile No.69)''. Leatherhead, Surrey, UK: Profile Publications Ltd., 1966.\n* Smith, J.Richard and Kay, Anthony. ''German Aircraft of the Second World War''. London: Putnam & Company Ltd., 1972 (third impression 1978). {{ISBN|0-370-00024-2}}.\n* Stachura, Petr; Bern\u00e1d, D\u00e9nes and Haladej, Dan. ''Henschel Hs 129'' (in Czech). Prague, Czech Republic: MBI, 1993 (second edition 1996 bilingual Czech/English). {{ISBN|80-901263-4-0}}.\n* Wood, Tony and Gunston, Bill. ''Hitler's Luftwaffe: A pictorial history and technical encyclopedia of Hitler's air power in World War II''. London: Salamander Books Ltd., 1977. {{ISBN|0-86101-005-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Henschel Hs 129}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160317053118/http://www.deutscheluftwaffe.de/archiv/Dokumente/ABC/h/Henschel/Hs%20192/Hs%20129%20B3%20-%207.5%20BK.pdf German WW II manual for Hs 129B-3's ''Bordkanone'' BK 7,5 cannon installation]\n\n{{Henschel aircraft}}\n{{RLM aircraft designations}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1930s German attack aircraft]]\n[[Category:Henschel aircraft|129]]\n[[Category:World War II ground attack aircraft of Germany]]\n[[Category:Low-wing aircraft]]\n[[Category:Aircraft first flown in 1939]]\n[[Category:Twin piston-engined tractor aircraft]]\n", "name_user": "Maury Markowitz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHs 129 B-2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henschel_Hs_129"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy Smith (wide receiver)", "text_new": "{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{other people||Jimmy Smith (disambiguation){{!}}Jimmy Smith}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Jimmy Smith\n|image=\n|caption=\n|position=[[Wide receiver]]\n|number=82\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1969|2|9}}\n|birth_place=[[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=1\n|weight_lbs=213\n|high_school=[[Callaway High School (Mississippi)|Callaway]] ([[Jackson, Mississippi]])\n|college=[[Jackson State Tigers football|Jackson State]]\n|draftyear=1992\n|draftround=2\n|draftpick=36\n|pastteams=\n* [[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|1992}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1993}})\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ({{NFL Year|1994}})*\n* [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] ({{NFL Year|1995}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2005}})\n|pastteamsnote=yes\n|highlights=\n* 2&times; [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XXVII|XXVII]], [[Super Bowl XXVIII|XXVIII]])\n* 5&times; [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1998 Pro Bowl|1997]]\u2013[[2002 Pro Bowl|2001]])\n* 2&times; Second-team [[Associated Press|AP]] [[All-Pro]] ([[1998 All-Pro Team|1998]], [[1999 All-Pro Team|1999]])\n* NFL Receptions leader (1999)\n*[[Pride of the Jaguars]]\n* Second-team [[Southwestern Athletic Conference|All-SWAC]] (1991)\n|statlabel1=[[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n|statvalue1=862\n|statlabel2=[[Receiving yards]]\n|statvalue2=12,287\n|statlabel3=[[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]]\n|statvalue3=67\n|nflnew=jimmysmith/2503028\n|pfr=SmitJi00 \n}}\n\n'''Jimmy Lee Smith Jr.''' (born February 9, 1969) is a former [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] in the [[National Football League]] for the [[Dallas Cowboys]] and [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Jackson State University]].\n\n==Early life==\nSmith is the son of Jimmy and Etta Smith. He attended [[Callaway High School (Jackson, Mississippi)|Callaway High School]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]]. He played [[wide receiver]] and earned All-conference honors as a senior.<ref name=\"jimmysmithathletics.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jimmysmithathletics.com/about_us.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 2, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141119213745/http://jimmysmithathletics.com/about_us.php |archivedate=November 19, 2014 }}</ref> He was given the nickname Silk by his teammates, for making the big plays look easy.\n\n==College career==\nSmith didn't have any Division I offers coming out of high school, so he accepted a football scholarship from [[Jackson State University]]. He was a backup wide receiver in his first 2 seasons.\n\nHe became a starter as a junior, teaming with [[Tim Barnett (American football)|Tim Barnett]] and becoming the top receiving duo in [[Division I-AA]], while registering 40 receptions (led the team) for 877 yards (21.3-yard average) and 9 [[touchdown]]s. Against [[Southern University]], he made 4 receptions for 184 yards and tied a school record with 3 receiving [[touchdown]]s (70,64 and 37 yards).\n\nIn his final year, he led the team with 43 catches for 801 yards (18.4-yard average) and 3 [[touchdown]]s. He finished his college career with 110 receptions, 2,073 yards and 16 [[touchdown]]s. Against [[Delaware State University]], he set a school record with 10 receptions for 239 yards, including a 71-yard [[touchdown]]. He graduated with a bachelor's degree in business administration.<ref name=\"jimmysmithathletics.com\"/>\n\nIn 2011, he was named to the [[Jackson State University]] All-Century team.\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Dallas Cowboys===\nSmith was selected by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] in the second round (36th overall) of the [[1992 NFL Draft]]. He missed the first four games after he broke his right [[fibula]] during the Dallas Blue-White Scrimmage on July 19. After missing ample time during the season, he was listed as the fourth wide receiver on the [[1992 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys']] depth chart, behind [[Michael Irvin]], [[Alvin Harper]], and [[Kelvin Martin (American football)|Kelvin Martin]]. On October 11, he made his professional regular season debut during a 27-0 victory over the [[1992 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]]. In a Week 16 matchup against the [[1992 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Smith had the highlight of his rookie year, tackling [[Deion Sanders]] during a punt return in a 41-17 victory. He played in just seven games as a special teamer, without registering a reception. The Cowboys finished first in the [[NFC East]] with a 13-3 record. On January 10, 1993, he appeared in his first career playoff game during the Cowboys 34-10 win over the [[1992 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], playing on [[special teams]]. Smith earned the first ring of his career as a rookie, after the Cowboys went on to [[Super Bowl XXVII]] and defeated the [[1992 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] 52-17.\n\nIn [[1993 Dallas Cowboys season|1993]], he was leading the team in pre-season (13) and receiving yards (197), while competing for the role as the third wide receiver that was left open with the departure in [[free agency]] of [[Kelvin Martin (American football)|Kelvin Martin]], behind Irvin and Harper. On August 21, Smith began feeling a pain in his abdominal area and brought it to the attention of two trainers and the team doctor, J.D. Zamarano, and was given [[Pepto Bismol]], [[Maalox]], and [[Tagamet]]. He played in the next preseason game and caught a touchdown reception, and was waved back in by a coach after taking himself out from taking a hit to the abdominal area that worsened the pain. Over the next few days he repeatedly brought the pain to the attention of the trainers and wasn't given adequate care or the correct diagnosis. He asked to be directed to a doctor and was told to see the team doctor who gave him a check up and took him to see the team surgeon that finally diagnosed him with [[appendicitis]]. On August 24, 1993, he underwent an emergency [[appendectomy]] surgery. The following day, he was released from the hospital by the surgeon although he had a 102.5 degree fever. On August 27, Smith was readmitted into the hospital after he woke up in severe pain with his stomach bloated and was vomiting, because of a severe post-surgical infection that was nearly fatal. He went into emergency surgery for an [[Ileostomy]], where they dissect and removed his intestine then substituted an external bag to collect his fecal matter, forcing Smith to miss the entire season, including [[Super Bowl XXVIII]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=20000123&id=fjofAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5s8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2065,2664744&hl=en | title=Detours don't stop Jacksonville's Smith | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> On October 2, the Cowboys placed him on the non-football illness list and opted not to pay his entire $350,000 salary for the 1993 season, as well as his insurance, pension, and free agent credits, making Smith instead an offer of $100,000 and no credits, which he declined.<ref>{{cite web| title=ANATOMY OF AN NFL GRIEVANCE: JIMMY SMITH VS. DALLAS COWBOYS | URL=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1993/12/19/anatomy-of-an-nfl-grievance-jimmy-smith-vs-dallas-cowboys/6b4b34be-eab9-4eec-863d-e15a2e414b40/| accessdate=January 7, 2018| website=washingtonpost.com| author=Bill Brubaker}}</ref> The NFL Player's Association filed a grievance with the Cowboys on the behalf of Smith, alleging he was due his full salary, which he won after going through arbitration.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/12/24/sports/sports-people-pro-football-cowboy-owner-loses.html | title=Cowboy Owner Loses | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 11, [[1994 Dallas Cowboys season|1994]], he was waived after refusing to take a pay cut.\n\n===Philadelphia Eagles===\nOn July 19, [[1994 Philadelphia Eagles season|1994]], he was signed as a [[free agent]] by the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], but was eventually released on August 30.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/31/sports/transactions-108855.html | title=Transactions | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Jacksonville Jaguars===\nOn February 28, 1995, Smith was signed by the expansion [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] after a tryout.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/03/01/sports/transactions-400095.html | title=Transactions | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He made the team after [[head coach]] [[Tom Coughlin]] saw his talents.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4090836 | title=Ex-Jag J. Smith found with drugs in car | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He competed with [[Desmond Howard]], [[Ernest Givens]], [[Willie Jackson (American football)|Willie Jackson]], [[Cedric Tillman (Denver Broncos)|Cedric Tillman]], and [[Curtis Marsh, Sr.|Curtis Marsh]] throughout training camp for a job as a starting wide receiver. Head coach [[Tom Coughlin]] named him the fifth wide receiver on the depth chart behind Howard, Givens, Jackson, and Tillman. He finished the season leading the Jaguars in kickoff returns.\n\nThe next year, he became a starter after [[Andre Rison]] was released following the 11th game against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]. He would emerge as a dominant receiver, finishing with 1,244 receiving yards (led the [[American Football Conference|AFC]]) and 7 [[touchdown]]s, while helping the team win its last five games and reach the [[American Football Conference|AFC]] Championship Game.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.jacksonville.com/sports/2016-12-09/jaguars-set-honor-jimmy-smith-who-continues-battle-never-ends | title=Jaguars set to honor Jimmy Smith, who continues a battle that never ends | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSmith would remain one of the cornerstones of the franchise for a decade. His teammates gave him the nickname J-Smooth and would later be known with [[Keenan McCardell]] as \"Thunder and Lightning\", after a [[TV Guide]] photo shoot in [[1997 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1997]]. Their history together was detailed in [[NFL Film]]'s 2014 [[A Football Life]]: \"Keenan McCardell & Jimmy Smith\".\n\nSmith continued to be a key member of the Jaguars offense and helped lead the team to playoff appearances for four straight years ([[1996 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1996]]\u2013[[1999 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1999]]). In [[1999 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1999]], he helped make the Jaguars the best team in the [[NFL]] during the regular season, registering 1,636 receiving yards and 6 [[touchdown]]s.\n\nIn [[2000 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2000]], his best career game came against arguably one of the best defenses in NFL history, when he posted 15 receptions, 291 receiving yards (fifth in NFL history) and 3 touchdowns, against the eventual [[Super Bowl]] champion the [[Baltimore Ravens]].\n\nIn [[2001 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2001]], he overcame three difficult intestine operations during the offseason, to remove scar tissue related to the appendectomy procedure he underwent in Dallas.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2001-05-18/sports/0105180320_1_jacksonville-jaguars-jimmy-smith-play-this-season | title=When Football Doesn't Matter | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> On November 26, he was found to have [[benzoylecgonine]] (a by-product of [[cocaine]]) in his system after being pulled over on suspicion of [[drunk driving]]. He denied using cocaine and was not charged with any crime since he was not found to be impaired while driving.<ref>[http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/112701/met_7931970.html Jags' Smith tests positive for cocaine in traffic stop]</ref> The incident placed him into the NFL's substance-abuse program.\n\nIn [[2003 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2003]], he was handed a four-game suspension for an undisclosed substance abuse violation.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2003-08-17/sports/0308170311_1_jimmy-smith-receiver-jimmy-jaguars | title=Smith Suspended 4 Games | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He would have a down year with 805 receiving yards and 4 [[touchdown]]s.\n\nOn May 11, [[2006 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2006]], Smith abruptly retired from the [[NFL]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2006-05-12/sports/JAGS12_1_jimmy-smith-jaguars-smith-contract | title=Jimmy Smith calling it quits | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He finished his career seventh in NFL history with 862 catches and 11th in league history with 12,287 yards. He had 67 career touchdown catches with the Jaguars. Smith had been voted to the [[Pro Bowl]] five straight times from [[1998 Pro Bowl|1997]] to [[2002 Pro Bowl|2001]]. He is also the Jacksonville Jaguars all-time leading receiver, having led the team in receiving every season from 1996-[[2005 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2005]]. He set team records with 116 [[Reception (American football)|receptions]] (also led the league) and 1,636 yards in [[1999 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1999]], both career-highs. His career-high in [[touchdown]]s was eight, achieved in [[1998 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1998]], [[2000 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2000]] and [[2001 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2001]].\n\nIn 2016, he was inducted into the Pride of the Jaguars (the franchise's ring of honor).\n\n===NFL records===\n* Most games with at least 5 receptions in a season - 16 (every game in 2001) Since tied by [[Antonio Brown]] and [[Pierre Gar\u00e7on]].\n* Most consecutive games with at least 5 receptions - 21. Since broken by Antonio Brown.\n* Most games with at least 49 receiving yards in a season - 16 (every game in 2001)\n\n===Jaguars franchise records===\n{{As of|2017}}'s NFL off-season, Jimmy Smith held at least 31 Jaguars franchise records, including:\n* Receptions: career (862), season (116 in 1999)\n* Receiving Yds: career (12,287), season (1,636 in 1999), game (291 on 2000-09-10 @BAL), playoffs (647), playoff season (228 in 1999), playoff game (136 on 2000-01-15 MIA)\n* Yds/Rec: career (14.25), playoffs (16.18), playoff season (22.8 in 1999), playoff game (27.2 on 2000-01-15 MIA)\n* Receiving TDs: career (67), game (3 on 2000-09-10 @BAL), playoffs (7), playoff season (3 in 1998), playoff game (2 on 2000-01-15 MIA)\n* Rec Yds/Game: career (71.9), playoffs (71.9), playoff season (114 in 1999)\n* Total TDs: playoffs (7), playoff season (3 in 1998), playoff game (2 on 2000-01-15 MIA)\n* Yds from Scrimmage: game (291 on 2000-09-10 @BAL)\n* 100+ yard receiving games: career (48), season (10 in 1999), playoffs (2)\n* Games with 1+ TD scored: career (64), playoffs (5)\n* Games with 2+ TD scored: playoffs (2)\n* 1000+ receiving yard seasons: career (9)\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! Games !! Receptions !! Yards !! Yards per Reception !! Longest Receptions !! Touchdowns !! First Downs !! Fumbles !! Fumbles Lost\n|-\n| [[1992 NFL season|1992]] || [[1992 Dallas Cowboys season|DAL]] || 7 || 0 || 0 || NA || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[1993 NFL season|1993]] || [[1993 Dallas Cowboys season|DAL]] || 0 || 0 || 0 || NA || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[1995 NFL season|1995]] || [[1995 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 22 || 288 || 13.1 || 33 || 3 || 12 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| [[1996 NFL season|1996]] || [[1996 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 83 || 1,244 || 15.0 || 62 || 7 || 60 || 1 || 1\n|-\n| [[1997 NFL season|1997]] || [[1997 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 82 || 1,324 || 16.1 || 75 || 4 || 64 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[1998 NFL season|1998]] || [[1998 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 78 || 1,182 || 15.2 || 72 || 8 || 50 || 2 || 1\n|-\n| [[1999 NFL season|1999]] || [[1999 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 116 || 1,636 || 14.1 || 62 || 6 || 86 || 1 || 1\n|-\n| [[2000 NFL season|2000]] || [[2000 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 15 || 91 || 1,213 || 13.3 || 65 || 8 || 60 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[2001 NFL season|2001]] || [[2001 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 112 || 1,373 || 12.3 || 35 || 8 || 68 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[2002 NFL season|2002]] || [[2002 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 80 || 1,027 || 12.8 || 47 || 7 || 53 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2003 NFL season|2003]] || [[2003 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 12 || 54 || 805 || 14.9 || 67 || 4 || 38 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[2004 NFL season|2004]] || [[2004 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]|| 16 || 74 || 1,172 || 15.8 || 65 || 6 || 52 || 2 || 1\n|-\n| [[2005 NFL season|2005]] || [[2005 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 70 || 1,023 || 14.6 || 45 || 6 || 56 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| Career || || 171 || 862 || 12,287 || 14.3 || 75 || 67 || 599 || 12 || 4\n|}<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|title=Jimmy Smith Stats|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/278/jimmy-smith|website=ESPN|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSmith and his wife Sandra currently reside in his hometown of Jackson, Mississippi with their five children, Jimmy III (\"Trey\"), Jaden, Dalys, Dyson and Jayse.<ref name=\"jimmysmithathletics.com\"/> In September 2014, Trey accepted a football scholarship to the [[University of Louisville]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000388513/article/trey-smith-exnfl-wr-jimmy-smiths-son-commits-to-louisville | title=Trey Smith, ex-NFL WR Jimmy Smith's son, commits to Louisville | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> Trey late transferred to the [[Wyoming Cowboys]] where he is a key contributor.\n\nHis father Jimmy Smith Sr. played [[linebacker]] for the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] in [[1968 Cincinnati Bengals season|1968]]. His popularity led some sushi restaurants in Jacksonville, Florida to honor him with a specialty sushi roll known as \"The Jimmy Smith Roll\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.jaxdailyrecord.com/article/city-notes-824 | title = City Notes | author = Daily Record Editor | language= | publisher = Financial News and Daily Record | date = August 25, 2009 | accessdate = March 7, 2018}}</ref> The roll consists of \"smoked salmon, cream cheese,scallions and crabstick deep fried with spicy mayo sauce\".  <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.jaxdailyrecord.com/article/city-notes-824 | title = City Notes | author = Daily Record Editor | language= | publisher = Financial News and Daily Record | date = August 25, 2009 | accessdate = March 7, 2018}}</ref>. Rolls bearing Jimmy Smith's name can still be found at many sushi restaurants in Jacksonville and the surrounding areas.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sushicafewinterpark.com/menu/53/ | title = Sushi Cafe Winter Park Menu | author = Sushi Cafe Winter park | language= | publisher = Sushi Cafe Winter Park | accessdate = March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nIn April 2009, Smith was arrested for multiple drug charges.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4090836 | title=Ex-Jag J. Smith found with drugs in car | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> Since then, he has been through rehab and made an effort to make a difference in other people's lives through the Jimmy Smith Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimmysmithathletics.com/blog/?cat=5 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207070614/http://www.jimmysmithathletics.com/blog/?cat=5 |archivedate=December 7, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Smith was sentenced to serve six years in the Mississippi Department of Corrections after being convicted of drug and weapons charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000169180/article/exjag-jimmy-smith-imprisoned-on-gun-drug-charges|title=Ex-Jag Jimmy Smith imprisoned on gun, drug charges|work=NFL.com|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref> According to Mississippi DOC records, he was scheduled to serve two years for \"possession of a firearm by a convicted felon\" and four years for possession of cocaine. He began his sentence on March 29, 2013. Although his tentative release date was November 8, 2018, he was released on July 2, 2013 on the condition of house arrest.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000215855/article/jimmy-smith-former-jacksonville-jaguar-out-of-prison | title = Jimmy Smith, former Jacksonville Jaguar, out of prison| author=Gregg Rosenthal | language= | publisher = [[NFL]] | date = July 2, 2013 | accessdate = March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090207065836/http://jimmysmithathletics.com/ Jimmy Smith Foundation and Athletics Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070205050924/http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=SMITHJIM08 Career Stats on Database Football]\n* [https://www.si.com/vault/2000/03/27/8115859/catching-fire-jaguars-wideout-jimmy-smith-having-rekindled-a-career-that-was-near-extinction-has-developed-into-a-receiver-nonpareil Catching Fire Jaguars wideout Jimmy Smith, having rekindled a career that was near extinction]\n\n{{Cowboys1992DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl XXVII}}\n{{Super Bowl XXVIII}}\n{{1995 Jacksonville Jaguars}}\n{{Pride of the Jaguars}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Jackson, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Jackson State Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Jaguars players]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{other people||Jimmy Smith (disambiguation){{!}}Jimmy Smith}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Jimmy Smith\n|image=\n|caption=\n|position=[[Wide receiver]]\n|number=82\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1969|2|9}}\n|birth_place=[[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=1\n|weight_lbs=213\n|high_school=[[Callaway High School (Mississippi)|Callaway]] ([[Jackson, Mississippi]])\n|college=[[Jackson State Tigers football|Jackson State]]\n|draftyear=1992\n|draftround=2\n|draftpick=36\n|pastteams=\n* [[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|1992}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1993}})\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ({{NFL Year|1994}})*\n* [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] ({{NFL Year|1995}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2005}})\n|pastteamsnote=yes\n|highlights=\n* 2&times; [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XXVII|XXVII]], [[Super Bowl XXVIII|XXVIII]])\n* 5&times; [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1998 Pro Bowl|1997]]\u2013[[2002 Pro Bowl|2001]])\n* 2&times; Second-team [[Associated Press|AP]] [[All-Pro]] ([[1998 All-Pro Team|1998]], [[1999 All-Pro Team|1999]])\n* NFL Receptions leader (1999)\n*[[Pride of the Jaguars]]\n* Second-team [[Southwestern Athletic Conference|All-SWAC]] (1991)\n|statlabel1=[[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n|statvalue1=862\n|statlabel2=[[Receiving yards]]\n|statvalue2=12,287\n|statlabel3=[[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]]\n|statvalue3=67\n|nflnew=jimmysmith/2503028\n|pfr=SmitJi00 \n}}\n\n'''Jimmy Lee Smith Jr.''' (born February 9, 1969) is a former [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] in the [[National Football League]] for the [[Dallas Cowboys]] and [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Jackson State University]].\n\n==Early life==\nSmith is the son of Jimmy and Etta Smith. He attended [[Callaway High School (Jackson, Mississippi)|Callaway High School]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]]. He played [[wide receiver]] and earned All-conference honors as a senior.<ref name=\"jimmysmithathletics.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jimmysmithathletics.com/about_us.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 2, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141119213745/http://jimmysmithathletics.com/about_us.php |archivedate=November 19, 2014 }}</ref> He was given the nickname Silk by his teammates, for making the big plays look easy.\n\n==College career==\nSmith didn't have any Division I offers coming out of high school, so he accepted a football scholarship from [[Jackson State University]]. He was a backup wide receiver in his first 2 seasons.\n\nHe became a starter as a junior, teaming with [[Tim Barnett (American football)|Tim Barnett]] and becoming the top receiving duo in [[Division I-AA]], while registering 40 receptions (led the team) for 877 yards (21.3-yard average) and 9 [[touchdown]]s. Against [[Southern University]], he made 4 receptions for 184 yards and tied a school record with 3 receiving [[touchdown]]s (70,64 and 37 yards).\n\nIn his final year, he led the team with 43 catches for 801 yards (18.4-yard average) and 3 [[touchdown]]s. He finished his college career with 110 receptions, 2,073 yards and 16 [[touchdown]]s. Against [[Delaware State University]], he set a school record with 10 receptions for 239 yards, including a 71-yard [[touchdown]]. He graduated with a bachelor's degree in business administration.<ref name=\"jimmysmithathletics.com\"/>\n\nIn 2011, he was named to the [[Jackson State University]] All-Century team.\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Dallas Cowboys===\nSmith was selected by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] in the second round (36th overall) of the [[1992 NFL Draft]]. He missed the first four games after he broke his right [[fibula]] during the Dallas Blue-White Scrimmage on July 19. After missing ample time during the season, he was listed as the fourth wide receiver on the [[1992 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys']] depth chart, behind [[Michael Irvin]], [[Alvin Harper]], and [[Kelvin Martin (American football)|Kelvin Martin]]. On October 11, he made his professional regular season debut during a 27-0 victory over the [[1992 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]]. In a Week 16 matchup against the [[1992 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Smith had the highlight of his rookie year, tackling [[Deion Sanders]] during a punt return in a 41-17 victory. He played in just seven games as a special teamer, without registering a reception. The Cowboys finished first in the [[NFC East]] with a 13-3 record. On January 10, 1993, he appeared in his first career playoff game during the Cowboys 34-10 win over the [[1992 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], playing on [[special teams]]. Smith earned the first ring of his career as a rookie, after the Cowboys went on to [[Super Bowl XXVII]] and defeated the [[1992 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] 52-17.\n\nIn [[1993 Dallas Cowboys season|1993]], he was leading the team in pre-season (13) and receiving yards (197), while competing for the role as the third wide receiver that was left open with the departure in [[free agency]] of [[Kelvin Martin (American football)|Kelvin Martin]], behind Irvin and Harper. On August 21, Smith began feeling a pain in his abdominal area and brought it to the attention of two trainers and the team doctor, J.D. Zamarano, and was given [[Pepto Bismol]], [[Maalox]], and [[Tagamet]]. He played in the next preseason game and caught a touchdown reception, and was waved back in by a coach after taking himself out from taking a hit to the abdominal area that worsened the pain. Over the next few days he repeatedly brought the pain to the attention of the trainers and wasn't given adequate care or the correct diagnosis. He asked to be directed to a doctor and was told to see the team doctor who gave him a check up and took him to see the team surgeon that finally diagnosed him with [[appendicitis]]. On August 24, 1993, he underwent an emergency [[appendectomy]] surgery. The following day, he was released from the hospital by the surgeon although he had a 102.5 degree fever. On August 27, Smith was readmitted into the hospital after he woke up in severe pain with his stomach bloated and was vomiting, because of a severe post-surgical infection that was nearly fatal. He went into emergency surgery for an [[Ileostomy]], where they dissect and removed his intestine then substituted an external bag to collect his fecal matter, forcing Smith to miss the entire season, including [[Super Bowl XXVIII]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=20000123&id=fjofAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5s8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2065,2664744&hl=en | title=Detours don't stop Jacksonville's Smith | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> On October 2, the Cowboys placed him on the non-football illness list and opted not to pay his entire $350,000 salary for the 1993 season, as well as his insurance, pension, and free agent credits, making Smith instead an offer of $100,000 and no credits, which he declined.<ref>{{cite web| title=ANATOMY OF AN NFL GRIEVANCE: JIMMY SMITH VS. DALLAS COWBOYS | URL=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1993/12/19/anatomy-of-an-nfl-grievance-jimmy-smith-vs-dallas-cowboys/6b4b34be-eab9-4eec-863d-e15a2e414b40/| accessdate=January 7, 2018| website=washingtonpost.com| author=Bill Brubaker}}</ref> The NFL Player's Association filed a grievance with the Cowboys on the behalf of Smith, alleging he was due his full salary, which he won after going through arbitration.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/12/24/sports/sports-people-pro-football-cowboy-owner-loses.html | title=Cowboy Owner Loses | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 11, [[1994 Dallas Cowboys season|1994]], he was waived after refusing to take a pay cut.\n\n===Philadelphia Eagles===\nOn July 19, [[1994 Philadelphia Eagles season|1994]], he was signed as a [[free agent]] by the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], but was eventually released on August 30.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/31/sports/transactions-108855.html | title=Transactions | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Jacksonville Jaguars===\nOn February 28, 1995, Smith was signed by the expansion [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] after a tryout.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/03/01/sports/transactions-400095.html | title=Transactions | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He made the team after [[head coach]] [[Tom Coughlin]] saw his talents.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4090836 | title=Ex-Jag J. Smith found with drugs in car | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He competed with [[Desmond Howard]], [[Ernest Givens]], [[Willie Jackson (American football)|Willie Jackson]], [[Cedric Tillman (Denver Broncos)|Cedric Tillman]], and [[Curtis Marsh, Sr.|Curtis Marsh]] throughout training camp for a job as a starting wide receiver. Head coach [[Tom Coughlin]] named him the fifth wide receiver on the depth chart behind Howard, Givens, Jackson, and Tillman. He finished the season leading the Jaguars in kickoff returns.\n\nThe next year, he became a starter after [[Andre Rison]] was released following the 11th game against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]. He would emerge as a dominant receiver, finishing with 1,244 receiving yards (led the [[American Football Conference|AFC]]) and 7 [[touchdown]]s, while helping the team win its last five games and reach the [[American Football Conference|AFC]] Championship Game.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.jacksonville.com/sports/2016-12-09/jaguars-set-honor-jimmy-smith-who-continues-battle-never-ends | title=Jaguars set to honor Jimmy Smith, who continues a battle that never ends | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSmith would remain one of the cornerstones of the franchise for a decade. His teammates gave him the nickname J-Smooth and would later be known with [[Keenan McCardell]] as \"Thunder and Lightning\", after a [[TV Guide]] photo shoot in [[1997 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1997]]. Their history together was detailed in [[NFL Film]]'s 2014 [[A Football Life]]: \"Keenan McCardell & Jimmy Smith\".\n\nSmith continued to be a key member of the Jaguars offense and helped lead the team to playoff appearances for four straight years ([[1996 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1996]]\u2013[[1999 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1999]]). In [[1999 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1999]], he helped make the Jaguars the best team in the [[NFL]] during the regular season, registering 1,636 receiving yards and 6 [[touchdown]]s.\n\nIn [[2000 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2000]], his best career game came against arguably one of the best defenses in NFL history, when he posted 15 receptions, 291 receiving yards (fifth in NFL history) and 3 touchdowns, against the eventual [[Super Bowl]] champion the [[Baltimore Ravens]].\n\nIn [[2001 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2001]], he overcame three difficult intestine operations during the offseason, to remove scar tissue related to the appendectomy procedure he underwent in Dallas.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2001-05-18/sports/0105180320_1_jacksonville-jaguars-jimmy-smith-play-this-season | title=When Football Doesn't Matter | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> On November 26, he was found to have [[benzoylecgonine]] (a by-product of [[cocaine]]) in his system after being pulled over on suspicion of [[drunk driving]]. He denied using cocaine and was not charged with any crime since he was not found to be impaired while driving.<ref>[http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/112701/met_7931970.html Jags' Smith tests positive for cocaine in traffic stop]</ref> The incident placed him into the NFL's substance-abuse program.\n\nIn [[2003 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2003]], he was handed a four-game suspension for an undisclosed substance abuse violation.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2003-08-17/sports/0308170311_1_jimmy-smith-receiver-jimmy-jaguars | title=Smith Suspended 4 Games | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He would have a down year with 805 receiving yards and 4 [[touchdown]]s.\n\nOn May 11, [[2006 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2006]], Smith abruptly retired from the [[NFL]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2006-05-12/sports/JAGS12_1_jimmy-smith-jaguars-smith-contract | title=Jimmy Smith calling it quits | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He finished his career seventh in NFL history with 862 catches and 11th in league history with 12,287 yards. He had 67 career touchdown catches with the Jaguars. Smith had been voted to the [[Pro Bowl]] five straight times from [[1998 Pro Bowl|1997]] to [[2002 Pro Bowl|2001]]. He is also the Jacksonville Jaguars all-time leading receiver, having led the team in receiving every season from 1996-[[2005 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2005]]. He set team records with 116 [[Reception (American football)|receptions]] (also led the league) and 1,636 yards in [[1999 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1999]], both career-highs. His career-high in [[touchdown]]s was eight, achieved in [[1998 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1998]], [[2000 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2000]] and [[2001 Jacksonville Jaguars season|2001]].\n\nIn 2016, he was inducted into the Pride of the Jaguars (the franchise's ring of honor).\n\n===NFL records===\n* Most games with at least 5 receptions in a season - 16 (every game in 2001) Since tied by [[Antonio Brown]] and [[Pierre Gar\u00e7on]].\n* Most consecutive games with at least 5 receptions - 21. Since broken by Antonio Brown.\n* Most games with at least 49 receiving yards in a season - 16 (every game in 2001)\n\n===Jaguars franchise records===\n{{As of|2017}}'s NFL off-season, Jimmy Smith held at least 31 Jaguars franchise records, including:\n* Receptions: career (862), season (116 in 1999)\n* Receiving Yds: career (12,287), season (1,636 in 1999), game (291 on 2000-09-10 @BAL), playoffs (647), playoff season (228 in 1999), playoff game (136 on 2000-01-15 MIA)\n* Yds/Rec: career (14.25), playoffs (16.18), playoff season (22.8 in 1999), playoff game (27.2 on 2000-01-15 MIA)\n* Receiving TDs: career (67), game (3 on 2000-09-10 @BAL), playoffs (7), playoff season (3 in 1998), playoff game (2 on 2000-01-15 MIA)\n* Rec Yds/Game: career (71.9), playoffs (71.9), playoff season (114 in 1999)\n* Total TDs: playoffs (7), playoff season (3 in 1998), playoff game (2 on 2000-01-15 MIA)\n* Yds from Scrimmage: game (291 on 2000-09-10 @BAL)\n* 100+ yard receiving games: career (48), season (10 in 1999), playoffs (2)\n* Games with 1+ TD scored: career (64), playoffs (5)\n* Games with 2+ TD scored: playoffs (2)\n* 1000+ receiving yard seasons: career (9)\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! Games !! Receptions !! Yards !! Yards per Reception !! Longest Receptions !! Touchdowns !! First Downs !! Fumbles !! Fumbles Lost\n|-\n| [[1992 NFL season|1992]] || [[1992 Dallas Cowboys season|DAL]] || 7 || 0 || 0 || NA || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[1993 NFL season|1993]] || [[1993 Dallas Cowboys season|DAL]] || 0 || 0 || 0 || NA || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[1995 NFL season|1995]] || [[1995 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 22 || 288 || 13.1 || 33 || 3 || 12 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| [[1996 NFL season|1996]] || [[1996 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 83 || 1,244 || 15.0 || 62 || 7 || 60 || 1 || 1\n|-\n| [[1997 NFL season|1997]] || [[1997 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 82 || 1,324 || 16.1 || 75 || 4 || 64 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[1998 NFL season|1998]] || [[1998 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 89 || 1,182 || 15.2 || 72 || 8 || 50 || 2 || 1\n|-\n| [[1999 NFL season|1999]] || [[1999 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 116 || 1,636 || 14.1 || 62 || 6 || 86 || 1 || 1\n|-\n| [[2000 NFL season|2000]] || [[2000 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 15 || 91 || 1,213 || 13.3 || 65 || 8 || 60 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[2001 NFL season|2001]] || [[2001 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 112 || 1,373 || 12.3 || 35 || 8 || 68 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[2002 NFL season|2002]] || [[2002 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 80 || 1,027 || 12.8 || 47 || 7 || 53 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2003 NFL season|2003]] || [[2003 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 12 || 54 || 805 || 14.9 || 67 || 4 || 38 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| [[2004 NFL season|2004]] || [[2004 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]|| 16 || 74 || 1,172 || 15.8 || 65 || 6 || 52 || 2 || 1\n|-\n| [[2005 NFL season|2005]] || [[2005 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]] || 16 || 70 || 1,023 || 14.6 || 45 || 6 || 56 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| Career || || 171 || 862 || 12,287 || 14.3 || 75 || 67 || 599 || 12 || 4\n|}<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|title=Jimmy Smith Stats|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/278/jimmy-smith|website=ESPN|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSmith and his wife Sandra currently reside in his hometown of Jackson, Mississippi with their five children, Jimmy III (\"Trey\"), Jaden, Dalys, Dyson and Jayse.<ref name=\"jimmysmithathletics.com\"/> In September 2014, Trey accepted a football scholarship to the [[University of Louisville]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000388513/article/trey-smith-exnfl-wr-jimmy-smiths-son-commits-to-louisville | title=Trey Smith, ex-NFL WR Jimmy Smith's son, commits to Louisville | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> Trey late transferred to the [[Wyoming Cowboys]] where he is a key contributor.\n\nHis father Jimmy Smith Sr. played [[linebacker]] for the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] in [[1968 Cincinnati Bengals season|1968]]. His popularity led some sushi restaurants in Jacksonville, Florida to honor him with a specialty sushi roll known as \"The Jimmy Smith Roll\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.jaxdailyrecord.com/article/city-notes-824 | title = City Notes | author = Daily Record Editor | language= | publisher = Financial News and Daily Record | date = August 25, 2009 | accessdate = March 7, 2018}}</ref> The roll consists of \"smoked salmon, cream cheese,scallions and crabstick deep fried with spicy mayo sauce\".  <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.jaxdailyrecord.com/article/city-notes-824 | title = City Notes | author = Daily Record Editor | language= | publisher = Financial News and Daily Record | date = August 25, 2009 | accessdate = March 7, 2018}}</ref>. Rolls bearing Jimmy Smith's name can still be found at many sushi restaurants in Jacksonville and the surrounding areas.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sushicafewinterpark.com/menu/53/ | title = Sushi Cafe Winter Park Menu | author = Sushi Cafe Winter park | language= | publisher = Sushi Cafe Winter Park | accessdate = March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\nIn April 2009, Smith was arrested for multiple drug charges.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=4090836 | title=Ex-Jag J. Smith found with drugs in car | accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref> Since then, he has been through rehab and made an effort to make a difference in other people's lives through the Jimmy Smith Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jimmysmithathletics.com/blog/?cat=5 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207070614/http://www.jimmysmithathletics.com/blog/?cat=5 |archivedate=December 7, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Smith was sentenced to serve six years in the Mississippi Department of Corrections after being convicted of drug and weapons charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000169180/article/exjag-jimmy-smith-imprisoned-on-gun-drug-charges|title=Ex-Jag Jimmy Smith imprisoned on gun, drug charges|work=NFL.com|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref> According to Mississippi DOC records, he was scheduled to serve two years for \"possession of a firearm by a convicted felon\" and four years for possession of cocaine. He began his sentence on March 29, 2013. Although his tentative release date was November 8, 2018, he was released on July 2, 2013 on the condition of house arrest.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000215855/article/jimmy-smith-former-jacksonville-jaguar-out-of-prison | title = Jimmy Smith, former Jacksonville Jaguar, out of prison| author=Gregg Rosenthal | language= | publisher = [[NFL]] | date = July 2, 2013 | accessdate = March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090207065836/http://jimmysmithathletics.com/ Jimmy Smith Foundation and Athletics Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070205050924/http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=SMITHJIM08 Career Stats on Database Football]\n* [https://www.si.com/vault/2000/03/27/8115859/catching-fire-jaguars-wideout-jimmy-smith-having-rekindled-a-career-that-was-near-extinction-has-developed-into-a-receiver-nonpareil Catching Fire Jaguars wideout Jimmy Smith, having rekindled a career that was near extinction]\n\n{{Cowboys1992DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl XXVII}}\n{{Super Bowl XXVIII}}\n{{1995 Jacksonville Jaguars}}\n{{Pride of the Jaguars}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Jackson, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Jackson State Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Jaguars players]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n", "name_user": "WakandaForever188", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNFL statistics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Smith_(wide_receiver)"}
{"title_page": "Future The DAGON", "text_new": "{{db-club|help=off}}\n{{Infobox organization\n |name                = Future The DAGON\n |native_name_lang    = \u1012\u1002\u102f\u1036\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a\u1000\u103b\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a\u1038\u101e\u102c\u1038\u1000\u103b\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a\u1038\u101e\u1030\u1019\u103b\u102c\u1038\u1021\u101e\u1004\u103a\u1038\n |logo                = Future The DAGON Logo.png\n |abbreviation        = FTD\n |motto               = Your dreams, your success, your Future The DAGON\n |founder             = Ko Min Thukha Kyaw\n |leader_title        = President\n |leader_name         = Ko Htoo Wai Lin\n |board_of_directors  = *Ko Htoo Wai Lin ([[Psychology]])\n*Ma Hnin Yu Yu Htwe ([[Law]])\n*Ko Chan Myae Htun([[Mathematics]])\n*Ko Zwe Yan Naung ([[Psycology]])\n*Ma Shwe Yamin Oo ([[Chemistry]])\n*Ma Jue Jue Kyaw ([[Philosophy]])\n*Ko Thant Zin Aung ([[Geography]])\n*Ko Kaung Htet Win Thant ([[Biochemistry]])\n*Ko Myint Aung ([[Law]])\n |type                = [[Non-govermental organization]]\n |location            = [[Dagon]]\n |membership          = 250 (2019)\n |parent_organization = [[Dagon University]]\n |website             = {{url|https://www.futurethedagon.ga}}\n}}\n'''Future The DAGON ('''{{Lang-my|[[\u1012\u1002\u102f\u1036\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a]]\u1000\u103b\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a\u1038\u101e\u102c\u1038\u104a\u1000\u103b\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a\u1038\u101e\u1030\u1019\u103b\u102c\u1038\u1021\u101e\u1004\u103a\u1038}})was founded in December , 2015.It  is one of the Non-gvernmental Organizations (NGO) in Yangon.It is responsible for [[Dagon University]] to be smart university.\n\n==History==\nIn December 2015,Future The DAGON is founded as [[Dagon University]] students network.Later in June 2017, this was legally organized as a organization.\n\n== Five Policies==\n1.To advance the interest & rights of students;\n\n2.To achieve an education system that can generate qualify students;\n\n3.To establish a modern university campus;\n\n4.To be in existence as an independent Students' Union and\n\n5.To flourish the culture and identity of any ethnic student in the interior university campus.\n\n== Leadership==\nFuture The DAGON elects its leadership democratically, with leaders of the organisation serving for one year terms in accordance with the Future The DAGON constitution. Ko Min Thukha Kyaw is the founder of Future The DAGON.The following is the list of the organisation\u2019s current leaders who were elected in Future The DAGON\u2019s Conference convened on 18 February 2020, to serve for a year executive term.\n*Ko Htoo Wai Lin ([[Psychology]])\n*Ma Hnin Yu Yu Htwe ([[Law]])\n*Ko Chan Myae Htun([[Mathematics]])\n*Ko Zwe Yan Naung ([[Psycology]])\n*Ma Shwe Yamin Oo ([[Chemistry]])\n*Ma Jue Jue Kyaw ([[Philosophy]])\n*Ko Thant Zin Aung ([[Geography]])\n*Ko Kaung Htet Win Thant ([[Biochemistry]])\n*Ko Myint Aung ([[Law]])\n\n==Activities==\nCurrently, Future The DAGON is carrying out the following activities.\n*[[Dagon University]] activities\n*Education activites\n*Social activities\n*Planning the activity programmes for future activit\n\n==See Also==\n* [[Dagon University]]\n* [[University of Distance Education, Yangon]]\n* [[All Burma Federation of Student Unions]]\n\n== External Links ==\n*[http://www.facebook.com/futurethedagon/ Official Facebook Page]\n*[http://www.instagram.com/futurethedagon/ Official Instagram]\n\n==References==\n*[https://m.facebook.com/story/graphql_permalink/?graphql_id=UzpfSTg5OTQzMTk5MzQ0MDM4NzoyMzQ5NzU2MTU4NDA3OTU2/ Cherry water festival organized by Future The DAGON]]\n*[http://www.futurethedagon.ga/ Official Web Site]\n*[http://www.findglocal.com/MM/Yangon/1822040198017540/Future-The-DAGON/ Future The DAGON in Find Glocal]\n*[https://www.glunis.com/MM/Yangon/1822040198017540/Future-The-DAGON/ Future The DAGON in GLUNIS]\n*[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=pMWoghYfc-Q/ DUSU Conference]\n*[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=kV0oL5Iv8_U/Dagon University Water Festival]\n*[https://www.mmtimes.com/news/students-offer-help-canteen-children.html/Students Offer Help Canteen Children]\n[[Category: Organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{db-club|help=off}}\n\n'''Future The DAGON ('''{{Lang-my|[[\u1012\u1002\u102f\u1036\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a]]\u1000\u103b\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a\u1038\u101e\u102c\u1038\u104a\u1000\u103b\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a\u1038\u101e\u1030\u1019\u103b\u102c\u1038\u1021\u101e\u1004\u103a\u1038}})was founded in December , 2015.It  is one of the Non-gvernmental Organizations (NGO) in Yangon.It is responsible for [[Dagon University]] to be smart university.\n{{Infobox organization\n |name=Future The DAGON|\n native_name_lang=\u1012\u1002\u102f\u1036\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a\u1000\u103b\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a\u1038\u101e\u102c\u1038\u1000\u103b\u1031\u102c\u1004\u103a\u1038\u101e\u1030\u1019\u103b\u102c\u1038\u1021\u101e\u1004\u103a\u1038\n |logo= [[file:Future The DAGON Logo.png|thumb]]\n |abbreviation=FTD\n |motto= Your dreams , your success , your Future The DAGON \n |founder= Ko Min Thukha Kyaw\n |leader_title= President\n |leader_name= Ko Htoo Wai Lin\n |board_of_directors= *Ko Htoo Wai Lin ([[Psychology]])\n*Ma Hnin Yu Yu Htwe ([[Law]])\n*Ko Chan Myae Htun([[Mathematics]])\n*Ko Zwe Yan Naung ([[Psycology]])\n*Ma Shwe Yamin Oo ([[Chemistry]])\n*Ma Jue Jue Kyaw ([[Philosophy]])\n*Ko Thant Zin Aung ([[Geography]])\n*Ko Kaung Htet Win Thant ([[Biochemistry]])\n*Ko Myint Aung ([[Law]])\n |type= [[Non-govermental Organization]]\n |location=[[Dagon]]\n |membership= 250 (2019)\n |parent_organization= [[Dagon University]]\n |website=https://www.futurethedagon.ga}}\n\n==History==\nIn December 2015,Future The DAGON is founded as [[Dagon University]] students network.Later in June 2017, this was legally organized as a organization.\n\n== Five Policies==\n1.To advance the interest & rights of students;\n\n2.To achieve an education system that can generate qualify students;\n\n3.To establish a modern university campus;\n\n4.To be in existence as an independent Students' Union and\n\n5.To flourish the culture and identity of any ethnic student in the interior university campus.\n\n== Leadership==\nFuture The DAGON elects its leadership democratically, with leaders of the organisation serving for one year terms in accordance with the Future The DAGON constitution. Ko Min Thukha Kyaw is the founder of Future The DAGON.The following is the list of the organisation\u2019s current leaders who were elected in Future The DAGON\u2019s Conference convened on 18 February 2020, to serve for a year executive term.\n*Ko Htoo Wai Lin ([[Psychology]])\n*Ma Hnin Yu Yu Htwe ([[Law]])\n*Ko Chan Myae Htun([[Mathematics]])\n*Ko Zwe Yan Naung ([[Psycology]])\n*Ma Shwe Yamin Oo ([[Chemistry]])\n*Ma Jue Jue Kyaw ([[Philosophy]])\n*Ko Thant Zin Aung ([[Geography]])\n*Ko Kaung Htet Win Thant ([[Biochemistry]])\n*Ko Myint Aung ([[Law]])\n\n==Activities==\nCurrently, Future The DAGON is carrying out the following activities.\n*[[Dagon University]] activities\n*Education activites\n*Social activities\n*Planning the activity programmes for future activit\n\n==See Also==\n* [[Dagon University]]\n* [[University of Distance Education, Yangon]]\n* [[All Burma Federation of Student Unions]]\n\n== External Links ==\n*[http://www.facebook.com/futurethedagon/ Official Facebook Page]\n*[http://www.instagram.com/futurethedagon/ Official Instagram]\n\n==References==\n*[https://m.facebook.com/story/graphql_permalink/?graphql_id=UzpfSTg5OTQzMTk5MzQ0MDM4NzoyMzQ5NzU2MTU4NDA3OTU2/ Cherry water festival organized by Future The DAGON]]\n*[http://www.futurethedagon.ga/ Official Web Site]\n*[http://www.findglocal.com/MM/Yangon/1822040198017540/Future-The-DAGON/ Future The DAGON in Find Glocal]\n*[https://www.glunis.com/MM/Yangon/1822040198017540/Future-The-DAGON/ Future The DAGON in GLUNIS]\n*[https://m.youtub