{"title_page": "Thiazolidinedione", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n[[File:Thiazolidinedione functional group.svg|thumb|Functional group]]\n\nThe '''thiazolidinediones''' {{IPAc-en|\u03b8|a\u026a|.|\u0259|\u02cc|z|o\u028a|l|\u1d7b|d|i\u02d0|n|\u02c8|d|a\u026a|.|o\u028a|n}},  abbreviated as''' TZD''', also known as '''glitazones''' after the [[prototypical drug]] [[ciglitazone]],<ref name=Hulin>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hulin B, McCarthy PA, Gibbs EM |title=The glitazone family of antidiabetic agents |journal=Current Pharmaceutical Design |volume=2 |pages=85\u2013102 |year=1996 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IYn4Va7wtAoC&pg=PA86&dq=ciglitazone}}</ref> are a class of [[heterocyclic compounds]] consisting of a five-membered C<sub>3</sub>NS ring.  The term usually refers to a family of drugs used in the treatment of [[diabetes mellitus type 2]] that were introduced in the late 1990s.\n\n== Mechanism of action ==\nThiazolidinediones or TZDs act by activating [[peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor|PPAR]]s (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptors), a group of [[nuclear receptors]], specific for ''[[PPAR\u03b3]]'' (PPAR-gamma, PPARG). They are thus the PPARG agonists subset of [[PPAR agonist]]s. The endogenous [[ligand]]s for these receptors are free [[fatty acid]]s (FFAs) and [[eicosanoid]]s. When activated, the receptor binds to [[DNA]] in complex with the [[retinoid X receptor]] (RXR), another nuclear receptor, increasing [[Transcription (genetics)|transcription]] of a number of specific [[gene]]s and decreasing transcription of others. The main effect of expression and repression of specific genes is an increase in the storage of fatty acids in adipocytes, thereby decreasing the amount of fatty acids present in circulation{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}. As a result, cells become more dependent on the oxidation of [[carbohydrates]], more specifically [[glucose]], in order to yield energy for other cellular processes{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}.\n\n===PPAR\u03b3 transactivation===\n[[File:Transactivation upload.svg|thumb|Thiazolidinedione ligand dependent transactivation is responsible for the majority of anti-diabetic effects.]]\nThe activated PPAR/RXR [[Protein dimer|heterodimer]] binds to peroxisome proliferator [[hormone response element]]s upstream of target genes in complex with a number of [[coactivator (genetics)|coactivators]] such as [[nuclear receptor coactivator 1]] and [[CREB binding protein]], this causes upregulation of genes (for a full list see [[PPAR\u03b3]]):\n* [[Insulin resistance]] is decreased\n* [[Adipocyte]] differentiation is modified<ref name=\"pmid20158086\">{{cite journal |pmid=20158086 |year=2010 |last1=Waki |first1=H |title=Regulation of differentiation and hypertrophy of adipocytes and adipokine network by PPARgamma |journal=Nihon Rinsho |volume=68 |issue=2 |pages=210\u20136 |last2=Yamauchi |first2=T |last3=Kadowaki |first3=T }}</ref>\n* [[Vascular endothelial growth factor|VEGF]]-induced [[angiogenesis]] is inhibited<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1172/JCI15634 |pmid=12370270 |pmc=151148 |title=PPAR\u03b3 ligands inhibit primary tumor growth and metastasis by inhibiting angiogenesis |journal=Journal of Clinical Investigation |volume=110 |issue=7 |pages=923\u201332 |year=2002 |last1=Panigrahy |first1=Dipak |last2=Singer |first2=Samuel |last3=Shen |first3=Lucy Q. |last4=Butterfield |first4=Catherine E. |last5=Freedman |first5=Deborah A. |last6=Chen |first6=Emy J. |last7=Moses |first7=Marsha A. |last8=Kilroy |first8=Susan |last9=Duensing |first9=Stefan |last10=Fletcher |first10=Christopher |last11=Fletcher |first11=Jonathan A. |last12=Hlatky |first12=Lynn |last13=Hahnfeldt |first13=Philip |last14=Folkman |first14=Judah |last15=Kaipainen |first15=Arja }}</ref>\n* [[Leptin]] levels decrease (leading to an increased [[appetite]])\n* Levels of certain [[interleukin]]s (e.g. IL-6) fall\n* [[Antiproliferative]] action{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n* [[Adiponectin]] levels rise\n\nTZDs also increase the synthesis of certain proteins involved in fat and glucose metabolism, which reduces levels of certain types of lipids, and circulating free fatty acids. TZDs generally decrease triglycerides and increase high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL-C) and low-density lipoprotein cholesterol (LDL-C).  Although the increase in LDL-C may be more focused on the larger LDL particles, which may be less atherogenic, the clinical significance of this is currently unknown. Nonetheless, rosiglitazone, a certain glitazone, was suspended from allowed use by medical authorities in Europe, as it has been linked to an increased risk of heart attack and stroke.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhs.uk/news/2010/09September/Pages/rosiglitazone-avandia-drug-suspended-heart-risk.aspx|title=Avandia diabetes drug suspended|author=|date=2010-09-24|website=nhs.uk}}</ref>\n\n===PPAR\u03b3 transrepression===\n[[File:PPAR transrepression.svg|thumb|Thiazolidinedione ligand dependent transrepression mediates the majority of anti-inflammatory effects.]]\nBinding of PPAR\u03b3 to coactivators appears to reduce the levels of coactivators available for binding to pro-inflammatory transcription factors such as [[NF-\u03baB]]; this causes a decrease in transcription of a number of pro inflammatory genes, including various interleukins and tumour necrosis factors.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n== Members of the class ==\n[[File:Thiazolidinedione and rhodanine.svg|thumb|right|275px|The chemical structure of thiazolidinedione and rhodanine]]\nChemically, the members of this class are derivatives of the parent compound thiazolidinedione, and include:\n* [[Pioglitazone]] (Actos), France and Germany have suspended its sale after a study suggested the drug could raise the risk of bladder cancer.<ref>http://www.huliq.com/3257/diabetes-drug-actos-sales-suspended-france-and-germany{{full citation needed|date=March 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Rosiglitazone]] (Avandia), which was put under selling restrictions in the US and withdrawn from the market in Europe due to some studies suggesting an increased risk of cardiovascular events. Upon re-evaluation of new data in 2013, the FDA lifted the restrictions.\n* [[Lobeglitazone]] (Duvie), approved for use in Korea\n\nExperimental, failed and non-marketed agents include:\n* [[Ciglitazone]]\n* [[Darglitazone]]\n* [[Englitazone]]\n* [[Netoglitazone]]\n* [[Rivoglitazone]]\n* [[Troglitazone]] (Rezulin), withdrawn due to increased incidence of drug-induced [[hepatitis]].\n* Balaglitazone (DRF-2593) - developed by [[Dr Reddy's Laboratories]], discontinued during 2010-11 phase III trials as no better than available molecules.\n\nReplacing one oxygen atom in a thiazolidinedione with an atom of sulfur gives a [[rhodanine]].\n\n== Uses ==\nThe only approved use of the thiazolidinediones is in [[diabetes mellitus]] type 2. According to a 2014 [[Cochrane review|Cochrane systematic review]] of four [[randomized controlled trial]]s, PPAR\u03b3-agonists may be effective in preventing further [[stroke]]s in those who have already had a stroke or a [[transient ischemic attack]] (TIA) and may stabilize [[Atherosclerosis|atherosclerotic plaques]] in the [[carotid arteries]].<ref name=\"CochraneStroke\">{{cite journal|last=Liu|first=Jia|last2=Wang|first2=Lu-Ning|date=October 2015|title=Peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma agonists for preventing recurrent stroke and other vascular events in patients with stroke or transient ischaemic attack|journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|issue=10|pages=CD010693|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD010693.pub3|pmid=26511368}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nExperimental investigations on TZDs have been carried out since 2005 in [[polycystic ovary syndrome]] (PCOS), [[non-alcoholic steatohepatitis]] (NASH),<ref name=NASH>{{cite journal |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa060326 |pmid=17135584 |title=A Placebo-Controlled Trial of Pioglitazone in Subjects with Nonalcoholic Steatohepatitis |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |volume=355 |issue=22 |pages=2297\u2013307 |year=2006 |last1=Belfort |first1=Renata |last2=Harrison |first2=Stephen A. |last3=Brown |first3=Kenneth |last4=Darland |first4=Celia |last5=Finch |first5=Joan |last6=Hardies |first6=Jean |last7=Balas |first7=Bogdan |last8=Gastaldelli |first8=Amalia |last9=Tio |first9=Fermin |last10=Pulcini |first10=Joseph |last11=Berria |first11=Rachele |last12=Ma |first12=Jennie Z. |last13=Dwivedi |first13=Sunil |last14=Havranek |first14=Russell |last15=Fincke |first15=Chris |last16=Defronzo |first16=Ralph |last17=Bannayan |first17=George A. |last18=Schenker |first18=Steven |last19=Cusi |first19=Kenneth }}</ref><ref>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT00227110|Role of Pioglitazone in the Treatment of Non-alcoholic Steatohepatitis (NASH)}}</ref> [[psoriasis]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1368-5031.2005.00765.x |pmid=16494655 |title=Type 2 diabetes, psoriasis and thiazolidinediones |journal=International Journal of Clinical Practice |volume=60 |issue=3 |pages=362\u20133 |year=2006 |last1=Krentz |first1=A. J. |last2=Friedmann |first2=P. S. }}</ref> [[autism]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1186/1742-2094-4-3 |pmid=17207275 |pmc=1781426 |year=2007 |last1=Boris |first1=Marvin |title=Effect of pioglitazone treatment on behavioral symptoms in autistic children |journal=Journal of Neuroinflammation |volume=4 |pages=3 |last2=Kaiser |first2=Claudia C |last3=Goldblatt |first3=Allan |last4=Elice |first4=Michael W |last5=Edelson |first5=Stephen M |last6=Adams |first6=James B |last7=Feinstein |first7=Douglas L }}</ref> [[ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome]] (by VEGF inhibition in [[granulosa cell]]s),<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.fertnstert.2009.02.059 |pmid=19342033 |pmc=2847675 |title=Thiazolidinediones decrease vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) production by human luteinized granulosa cells in vitro |journal=Fertility and Sterility |volume=93 |issue=6 |pages=2042\u20137 |year=2010 |last1=Shah |first1=Divya K. |last2=Menon |first2=K.M.J. |last3=Cabrera |first3=Lourdes M. |last4=Vahratian |first4=Anjel |last5=Kavoussi |first5=Shahryar K. |last6=Lebovic |first6=Dan I. }}</ref> lichen planopilaris, and other conditions.<ref name=trials>[http://clinicaltrials.gov/ct/search?term=rosiglitazone&submit=Search Clinical Trials for Rosiglitazone] - from ClinicalTrials.gov, a service of the U.S. [[National Institutes of Health]]{{vs|should point to a specific page and not a list of search results|date=March 2015}}</ref>\n\nSeveral forms of [[lipodystrophy]] cause insulin resistance, which has responded favorably to thiazolidinediones. There are some indications that thiazolidinediones provide some degree of protection against the initial stages of [[breast carcinoma]] development.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nEvidence was emerging in 2008 that [[vitamin E]] with thiazolidinediones is effective in the treatment of [[Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease|non-alcoholic steatohepatitis]] due to their combined antioxidant and insulin sensitizing effects, producing histological improvements in [[steatosis]] severity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chitturi|first=Shivakumar|date=November 2008|title=Treatment Options for Nonalcoholic Fatty Liver Disease|journal=Therapeutic Advances in Gastroenterology |volume=1|issue=3|pages=173\u2013189|doi=10.1177/1756283X08096951|issn=1756-283X|pmc=3002502|pmid=21180527}}</ref>\n\n== Side effects and contraindications ==\nThe withdrawal of [[troglitazone]] has led to concerns of the other thiazolidinediones also increasing the incidence of [[hepatitis]] and potential liver failure, an approximately 1 in 20,000 individual occurrence with troglitazone. Because of this, the FDA recommends two to three month checks of [[liver enzyme]]s for the first year of thiazolidinedione therapy to check for this rare but potentially catastrophic complication. To date, 2008, the newer thiazolidinediones, [[rosiglitazone]] and [[pioglitazone]] have been free of this problem. WHY TF do you write smthg without a citation in wikipedia???{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nThe main side effect of all thiazolidinediones is water retention, leading to [[edema]], generally a problem in less than 5% of individuals, but a big problem for some and potentially, with significant water retention, leading to a decompensation of potentially previously unrecognized [[heart failure]]. Therefore, thiazolidinediones should be prescribed with both caution and patient warnings about the potential for water retention/weight gain, especially in patients with decreased ventricular function ([[New York Heart Association Functional Classification|NYHA]] grade III or IV heart failure).{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nThough older studies suggested there may be an increased risk of [[coronary heart disease]] and heart attacks with rosiglitazone,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbeslife/health/feeds/hscout/2007/08/14/hscout607350.html |title=Avandia to Carry Stronger Heart Failure Warning - Forbes.com |accessdate=2007-08-15 |website= |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071021074525/http://forbes.com/forbeslife/health/feeds/hscout/2007/08/14/hscout607350.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-10-21}}</ref> [[pioglitazone]] treatment, in contrast, has shown significant protection from both micro- and macro-vascular cardiovascular events and [[atheroma|plaque]] progression.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2337/diacare.27.7.1647 |pmid=15220241 |title=The Prospective Pioglitazone Clinical Trial in Macrovascular Events (PROactive): Can pioglitazone reduce cardiovascular events in diabetes? Study design and baseline characteristics of 5,238 patients |journal=Diabetes Care |volume=27 |issue=7 |pages=1647\u201353 |year=2004 |last1=Charbonnel |first1=B. |last2=Dormandy |first2=J. |last3=Erdmann |first3=E. |last4=Massi-Benedetti |first4=M. |last5=Skene |first5=A. |last6=Proactive Study |first6=Group }}</ref><ref name=\"Pioglitazone and cardiovascular risk\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1463-1326.2008.00892.x |pmid=18505403 |title=Pioglitazone and cardiovascular risk. A comprehensive meta-analysis of randomized clinical trials |journal=Diabetes, Obesity and Metabolism |volume=10 |issue=12 |pages=1221\u201338 |year=2008 |last1=Mannucci |first1=E. |last2=Monami |first2=M. |last3=Lamanna |first3=C. |last4=Gensini |first4=G. F. |last5=Marchionni |first5=N. }}</ref><ref name=\"Nissen\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/jama.299.13.1561 |pmid=18378631 |title=Comparison of Pioglitazone vs Glimepiride on Progression of Coronary Atherosclerosis in Patients with Type 2 Diabetes |journal=JAMA |volume=299 |issue=13 |pages=1561\u201373 |year=2008 |last1=Nissen |first1=Steven E. |last2=Nicholls |first2=Stephen J. |last3=Wolski |first3=Kathy |last4=Nesto |first4=Richard |last5=Kupfer |first5=Stuart |last6=Perez |first6=Alfonso |last7=Jure |first7=Horacio |last8=De Larochelli\u00e8re |first8=Robert |last9=Staniloae |first9=Cezar S. |last10=Mavromatis |first10=Kreton |last11=Saw |first11=Jacqueline |last12=Hu |first12=Bo |last13=Lincoff |first13=A. Michael |last14=Tuzcu |first14=E. Murat |last15=Periscope Investigators |first15=for the }}</ref> These studies led to a period of Food and Drug Administration advisories (2007 - 2013) that, aided by extensive media coverage, led to a substantial decrease in rosiglitazone use. In November 2013, the FDA announced it would remove the usage restrictions for rosiglitazone in patients with coronary artery disease.<ref>https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm376516.htm{{full citation needed|date=March 2015}}</ref> The new recommendations were largely based on the reasoning that prior meta-analyses leading to the original restrictions were not designed to assess cardiac outcomes and, thus, not uniformly collected or adjudicated.  In contrast, one of the largest trials (RECORD trial) that was specifically designed to assess cardiac outcomes found no increased risk of  [[myocardial infarction]] with rosiglitazone use, even after independent re-evaluation for FDA review.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.ahj.2013.05.004 |pmid=23895806 |title=Results of a reevaluation of cardiovascular outcomes in the RECORD trial |journal=American Heart Journal |volume=166 |issue=2 |pages=240\u2013249.e1 |year=2013 |last1=Mahaffey |first1=Kenneth W. |last2=Hafley |first2=Gail |last3=Dickerson |first3=Sheila |last4=Burns |first4=Shana |last5=Tourt-Uhlig |first5=Sandra |last6=White |first6=Jennifer |last7=Newby |first7=L. Kristin |last8=Komajda |first8=Michel |last9=McMurray |first9=John |last10=Bigelow |first10=Robert |last11=Home |first11=Philip D. |last12=Lopes |first12=Renato D. }}</ref>\n\nA 2013 [[meta-analysis]] concluded that use of [[pioglitazone]] is associated with a slightly higher risk of [[bladder cancer]] compared to the general population. The authors of the same analysis recommended that other blood sugar lowering agents be considered in people with other risk factors for bladder cancer such as [[cigarette smoking]], family history, or exposure to certain forms of [[chemotherapy]].<ref name=\"Ferwana2013\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Ferwana M, Firwana B, Hasan R, Al-Mallah MH, Kim S, Montori VM, Murad MH |title=Pioglitazone and risk of bladder cancer: a meta-analysis of controlled studies|journal=Diabetes Medicine|volume=30|issue=9|pages=1026\u201332|date=September 2013|pmid=23350856|doi=10.1111/dme.12144}}</ref>\n\nThiazolidinediones reduce [[bone mineral density]] and increase the risk of fractures in women, possibly as a result of biasing the differentiation of [[bone marrow stromal cells]] away from [[osteoblast]] differentiation and toward [[adipocyte]] formation.<ref name=\"Man&Dic2015\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Mannucci E, Dicembrini I |title=Drugs for type 2 diabetes: role in the regulation of bone metabolism|journal=Clin Cases Miner Bone Metab|date=May\u2013August 2015|volume=12|issue=2|pages=130\u2013134|doi=10.11138/ccmbm/2015.12.2.130|pmid=26604937|pmc=4625768}}</ref>\n\nThiazolidinediones increase expression of [[Angiotensin-converting enzyme 2|angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2)]]. It is hypothesized that this increases the chance of serious infection with the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] virus, which causes [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=\"FengKaraRoth2020\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Feng L, Karakiulakis G, Roth M|title=Are patients with hypertension and diabetes mellitus at increased risk for COVID-19 infection?|journal=The Lancet Respiratory Medicine|date=March 11, 2020|doi=10.1016/S2213-2600(20)30116-8}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Oral hypoglycemics}}\n{{PPAR modulators}}\n\n[[Category:Thiazolidinediones| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n[[File:Thiazolidinedione functional group.svg|thumb|Functional group]]\n\nThe '''thiazolidinediones''' {{IPAc-en|\u03b8|a\u026a|.|\u0259|\u02cc|z|o\u028a|l|\u1d7b|d|i\u02d0|n|\u02c8|d|a\u026a|.|o\u028a|n}},  abbreviated as''' TZD''', also known as '''glitazones''' after the [[prototypical drug]] [[ciglitazone]],<ref name=Hulin>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hulin B, McCarthy PA, Gibbs EM |title=The glitazone family of antidiabetic agents |journal=Current Pharmaceutical Design |volume=2 |pages=85\u2013102 |year=1996 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IYn4Va7wtAoC&pg=PA86&dq=ciglitazone}}</ref> are a class of [[heterocyclic compounds]] consisting of a five-membered C<sub>3</sub>NS ring.  The term usually refers to a family of drugs used in the treatment of [[diabetes mellitus type 2]] that were introduced in the late 1990s.\n\n== Mechanism of action ==\nThiazolidinediones or TZDs act by activating [[peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor|PPAR]]s (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptors), a group of [[nuclear receptors]], specific for ''[[PPAR\u03b3]]'' (PPAR-gamma, PPARG). They are thus the PPARG agonists subset of [[PPAR agonist]]s. The endogenous [[ligand]]s for these receptors are free [[fatty acid]]s (FFAs) and [[eicosanoid]]s. When activated, the receptor binds to [[DNA]] in complex with the [[retinoid X receptor]] (RXR), another nuclear receptor, increasing [[Transcription (genetics)|transcription]] of a number of specific [[gene]]s and decreasing transcription of others. The main effect of expression and repression of specific genes is an increase in the storage of fatty acids in adipocytes, thereby decreasing the amount of fatty acids present in circulation{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}. As a result, cells become more dependent on the oxidation of [[carbohydrates]], more specifically [[glucose]], in order to yield energy for other cellular processes{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}.\n\n===PPAR\u03b3 transactivation===\n[[File:Transactivation upload.svg|thumb|Thiazolidinedione ligand dependent transactivation is responsible for the majority of anti-diabetic effects.]]\nThe activated PPAR/RXR [[Protein dimer|heterodimer]] binds to peroxisome proliferator [[hormone response element]]s upstream of target genes in complex with a number of [[coactivator (genetics)|coactivators]] such as [[nuclear receptor coactivator 1]] and [[CREB binding protein]], this causes upregulation of genes (for a full list see [[PPAR\u03b3]]):\n* [[Insulin resistance]] is decreased\n* [[Adipocyte]] differentiation is modified<ref name=\"pmid20158086\">{{cite journal |pmid=20158086 |year=2010 |last1=Waki |first1=H |title=Regulation of differentiation and hypertrophy of adipocytes and adipokine network by PPARgamma |journal=Nihon Rinsho |volume=68 |issue=2 |pages=210\u20136 |last2=Yamauchi |first2=T |last3=Kadowaki |first3=T }}</ref>\n* [[Vascular endothelial growth factor|VEGF]]-induced [[angiogenesis]] is inhibited<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1172/JCI15634 |pmid=12370270 |pmc=151148 |title=PPAR\u03b3 ligands inhibit primary tumor growth and metastasis by inhibiting angiogenesis |journal=Journal of Clinical Investigation |volume=110 |issue=7 |pages=923\u201332 |year=2002 |last1=Panigrahy |first1=Dipak |last2=Singer |first2=Samuel |last3=Shen |first3=Lucy Q. |last4=Butterfield |first4=Catherine E. |last5=Freedman |first5=Deborah A. |last6=Chen |first6=Emy J. |last7=Moses |first7=Marsha A. |last8=Kilroy |first8=Susan |last9=Duensing |first9=Stefan |last10=Fletcher |first10=Christopher |last11=Fletcher |first11=Jonathan A. |last12=Hlatky |first12=Lynn |last13=Hahnfeldt |first13=Philip |last14=Folkman |first14=Judah |last15=Kaipainen |first15=Arja }}</ref>\n* [[Leptin]] levels decrease (leading to an increased [[appetite]])\n* Levels of certain [[interleukin]]s (e.g. IL-6) fall\n* [[Antiproliferative]] action{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n* [[Adiponectin]] levels rise\n\nTZDs also increase the synthesis of certain proteins involved in fat and glucose metabolism, which reduces levels of certain types of lipids, and circulating free fatty acids. TZDs generally decrease triglycerides and increase high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL-C) and low-density lipoprotein cholesterol (LDL-C).  Although the increase in LDL-C may be more focused on the larger LDL particles, which may be less atherogenic, the clinical significance of this is currently unknown. Nonetheless, rosiglitazone, a certain glitazone, was suspended from allowed use by medical authorities in Europe, as it has been linked to an increased risk of heart attack and stroke.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhs.uk/news/2010/09September/Pages/rosiglitazone-avandia-drug-suspended-heart-risk.aspx|title=Avandia diabetes drug suspended|author=|date=2010-09-24|website=nhs.uk}}</ref>\n\n===PPAR\u03b3 transrepression===\n[[File:PPAR transrepression.svg|thumb|Thiazolidinedione ligand dependent transrepression mediates the majority of anti-inflammatory effects.]]\nBinding of PPAR\u03b3 to coactivators appears to reduce the levels of coactivators available for binding to pro-inflammatory transcription factors such as [[NF-\u03baB]]; this causes a decrease in transcription of a number of pro inflammatory genes, including various interleukins and tumour necrosis factors.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n== Members of the class ==\n[[File:Thiazolidinedione and rhodanine.svg|thumb|right|275px|The chemical structure of thiazolidinedione and rhodanine]]\nChemically, the members of this class are derivatives of the parent compound thiazolidinedione, and include:\n* [[Pioglitazone]] (Actos), France and Germany have suspended its sale after a study suggested the drug could raise the risk of bladder cancer.<ref>http://www.huliq.com/3257/diabetes-drug-actos-sales-suspended-france-and-germany{{full citation needed|date=March 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Rosiglitazone]] (Avandia), which was put under selling restrictions in the US and withdrawn from the market in Europe due to some studies suggesting an increased risk of cardiovascular events. Upon re-evaluation of new data in 2013, the FDA lifted the restrictions.\n* [[Lobeglitazone]] (Duvie), approved for use in Korea\n\nExperimental, failed and non-marketed agents include:\n* [[Ciglitazone]]\n* [[Darglitazone]]\n* [[Englitazone]]\n* [[Netoglitazone]]\n* [[Rivoglitazone]]\n* [[Troglitazone]] (Rezulin), withdrawn due to increased incidence of drug-induced [[hepatitis]].\n* Balaglitazone (DRF-2593) - developed by [[Dr Reddy's Laboratories]], discontinued during 2010-11 phase III trials as no better than available molecules.\n\nReplacing one oxygen atom in a thiazolidinedione with an atom of sulfur gives a [[rhodanine]].\n\n== Uses ==\nThe only approved use of the thiazolidinediones is in [[diabetes mellitus]] type 2. According to a 2014 [[Cochrane review|Cochrane systematic review]] of four [[randomized controlled trial]]s, PPAR\u03b3-agonists may be effective in preventing further [[stroke]]s in those who have already had a stroke or a [[transient ischemic attack]] (TIA) and may stabilize [[Atherosclerosis|atherosclerotic plaques]] in the [[carotid arteries]].<ref name=\"CochraneStroke\">{{cite journal|last=Liu|first=Jia|last2=Wang|first2=Lu-Ning|date=October 2015|title=Peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma agonists for preventing recurrent stroke and other vascular events in patients with stroke or transient ischaemic attack|journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|issue=10|pages=CD010693|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD010693.pub3|pmid=26511368}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nExperimental investigations on TZDs have been carried out since 2005 in [[polycystic ovary syndrome]] (PCOS), [[non-alcoholic steatohepatitis]] (NASH),<ref name=NASH>{{cite journal |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa060326 |pmid=17135584 |title=A Placebo-Controlled Trial of Pioglitazone in Subjects with Nonalcoholic Steatohepatitis |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |volume=355 |issue=22 |pages=2297\u2013307 |year=2006 |last1=Belfort |first1=Renata |last2=Harrison |first2=Stephen A. |last3=Brown |first3=Kenneth |last4=Darland |first4=Celia |last5=Finch |first5=Joan |last6=Hardies |first6=Jean |last7=Balas |first7=Bogdan |last8=Gastaldelli |first8=Amalia |last9=Tio |first9=Fermin |last10=Pulcini |first10=Joseph |last11=Berria |first11=Rachele |last12=Ma |first12=Jennie Z. |last13=Dwivedi |first13=Sunil |last14=Havranek |first14=Russell |last15=Fincke |first15=Chris |last16=Defronzo |first16=Ralph |last17=Bannayan |first17=George A. |last18=Schenker |first18=Steven |last19=Cusi |first19=Kenneth }}</ref><ref>{{ClinicalTrialsGov|NCT00227110|Role of Pioglitazone in the Treatment of Non-alcoholic Steatohepatitis (NASH)}}</ref> [[psoriasis]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1368-5031.2005.00765.x |pmid=16494655 |title=Type 2 diabetes, psoriasis and thiazolidinediones |journal=International Journal of Clinical Practice |volume=60 |issue=3 |pages=362\u20133 |year=2006 |last1=Krentz |first1=A. J. |last2=Friedmann |first2=P. S. }}</ref> [[autism]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1186/1742-2094-4-3 |pmid=17207275 |pmc=1781426 |year=2007 |last1=Boris |first1=Marvin |title=Effect of pioglitazone treatment on behavioral symptoms in autistic children |journal=Journal of Neuroinflammation |volume=4 |pages=3 |last2=Kaiser |first2=Claudia C |last3=Goldblatt |first3=Allan |last4=Elice |first4=Michael W |last5=Edelson |first5=Stephen M |last6=Adams |first6=James B |last7=Feinstein |first7=Douglas L }}</ref> [[ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome]] (by VEGF inhibition in [[granulosa cell]]s),<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.fertnstert.2009.02.059 |pmid=19342033 |pmc=2847675 |title=Thiazolidinediones decrease vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) production by human luteinized granulosa cells in vitro |journal=Fertility and Sterility |volume=93 |issue=6 |pages=2042\u20137 |year=2010 |last1=Shah |first1=Divya K. |last2=Menon |first2=K.M.J. |last3=Cabrera |first3=Lourdes M. |last4=Vahratian |first4=Anjel |last5=Kavoussi |first5=Shahryar K. |last6=Lebovic |first6=Dan I. }}</ref> lichen planopilaris, and other conditions.<ref name=trials>[http://clinicaltrials.gov/ct/search?term=rosiglitazone&submit=Search Clinical Trials for Rosiglitazone] - from ClinicalTrials.gov, a service of the U.S. [[National Institutes of Health]]{{vs|should point to a specific page and not a list of search results|date=March 2015}}</ref>\n\nSeveral forms of [[lipodystrophy]] cause insulin resistance, which has responded favorably to thiazolidinediones. There are some indications that thiazolidinediones provide some degree of protection against the initial stages of [[breast carcinoma]] development.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nEvidence was emerging in 2008 that [[vitamin E]] with thiazolidinediones is effective in the treatment of [[Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease|non-alcoholic steatohepatitis]] due to their combined antioxidant and insulin sensitizing effects, producing histological improvements in [[steatosis]] severity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chitturi|first=Shivakumar|date=November 2008|title=Treatment Options for Nonalcoholic Fatty Liver Disease|journal=Therapeutic Advances in Gastroenterology |volume=1|issue=3|pages=173\u2013189|doi=10.1177/1756283X08096951|issn=1756-283X|pmc=3002502|pmid=21180527}}</ref>\n\n== Side effects and contraindications ==\nThe withdrawal of [[troglitazone]] has led to concerns of the other thiazolidinediones also increasing the incidence of [[hepatitis]] and potential liver failure, an approximately 1 in 20,000 individual occurrence with troglitazone. Because of this, the FDA recommends two to three month checks of [[liver enzyme]]s for the first year of thiazolidinedione therapy to check for this rare but potentially catastrophic complication. To date, 2008, the newer thiazolidinediones, [[rosiglitazone]] and [[pioglitazone]] have been free of this problem.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nThe main side effect of all thiazolidinediones is water retention, leading to [[edema]], generally a problem in less than 5% of individuals, but a big problem for some and potentially, with significant water retention, leading to a decompensation of potentially previously unrecognized [[heart failure]]. Therefore, thiazolidinediones should be prescribed with both caution and patient warnings about the potential for water retention/weight gain, especially in patients with decreased ventricular function ([[New York Heart Association Functional Classification|NYHA]] grade III or IV heart failure).{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nThough older studies suggested there may be an increased risk of [[coronary heart disease]] and heart attacks with rosiglitazone,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbeslife/health/feeds/hscout/2007/08/14/hscout607350.html |title=Avandia to Carry Stronger Heart Failure Warning - Forbes.com |accessdate=2007-08-15 |website= |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071021074525/http://forbes.com/forbeslife/health/feeds/hscout/2007/08/14/hscout607350.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-10-21}}</ref> [[pioglitazone]] treatment, in contrast, has shown significant protection from both micro- and macro-vascular cardiovascular events and [[atheroma|plaque]] progression.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2337/diacare.27.7.1647 |pmid=15220241 |title=The Prospective Pioglitazone Clinical Trial in Macrovascular Events (PROactive): Can pioglitazone reduce cardiovascular events in diabetes? Study design and baseline characteristics of 5,238 patients |journal=Diabetes Care |volume=27 |issue=7 |pages=1647\u201353 |year=2004 |last1=Charbonnel |first1=B. |last2=Dormandy |first2=J. |last3=Erdmann |first3=E. |last4=Massi-Benedetti |first4=M. |last5=Skene |first5=A. |last6=Proactive Study |first6=Group }}</ref><ref name=\"Pioglitazone and cardiovascular risk\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1463-1326.2008.00892.x |pmid=18505403 |title=Pioglitazone and cardiovascular risk. A comprehensive meta-analysis of randomized clinical trials |journal=Diabetes, Obesity and Metabolism |volume=10 |issue=12 |pages=1221\u201338 |year=2008 |last1=Mannucci |first1=E. |last2=Monami |first2=M. |last3=Lamanna |first3=C. |last4=Gensini |first4=G. F. |last5=Marchionni |first5=N. }}</ref><ref name=\"Nissen\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/jama.299.13.1561 |pmid=18378631 |title=Comparison of Pioglitazone vs Glimepiride on Progression of Coronary Atherosclerosis in Patients with Type 2 Diabetes |journal=JAMA |volume=299 |issue=13 |pages=1561\u201373 |year=2008 |last1=Nissen |first1=Steven E. |last2=Nicholls |first2=Stephen J. |last3=Wolski |first3=Kathy |last4=Nesto |first4=Richard |last5=Kupfer |first5=Stuart |last6=Perez |first6=Alfonso |last7=Jure |first7=Horacio |last8=De Larochelli\u00e8re |first8=Robert |last9=Staniloae |first9=Cezar S. |last10=Mavromatis |first10=Kreton |last11=Saw |first11=Jacqueline |last12=Hu |first12=Bo |last13=Lincoff |first13=A. Michael |last14=Tuzcu |first14=E. Murat |last15=Periscope Investigators |first15=for the }}</ref> These studies led to a period of Food and Drug Administration advisories (2007 - 2013) that, aided by extensive media coverage, led to a substantial decrease in rosiglitazone use. In November 2013, the FDA announced it would remove the usage restrictions for rosiglitazone in patients with coronary artery disease.<ref>https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm376516.htm{{full citation needed|date=March 2015}}</ref> The new recommendations were largely based on the reasoning that prior meta-analyses leading to the original restrictions were not designed to assess cardiac outcomes and, thus, not uniformly collected or adjudicated.  In contrast, one of the largest trials (RECORD trial) that was specifically designed to assess cardiac outcomes found no increased risk of  [[myocardial infarction]] with rosiglitazone use, even after independent re-evaluation for FDA review.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.ahj.2013.05.004 |pmid=23895806 |title=Results of a reevaluation of cardiovascular outcomes in the RECORD trial |journal=American Heart Journal |volume=166 |issue=2 |pages=240\u2013249.e1 |year=2013 |last1=Mahaffey |first1=Kenneth W. |last2=Hafley |first2=Gail |last3=Dickerson |first3=Sheila |last4=Burns |first4=Shana |last5=Tourt-Uhlig |first5=Sandra |last6=White |first6=Jennifer |last7=Newby |first7=L. Kristin |last8=Komajda |first8=Michel |last9=McMurray |first9=John |last10=Bigelow |first10=Robert |last11=Home |first11=Philip D. |last12=Lopes |first12=Renato D. }}</ref>\n\nA 2013 [[meta-analysis]] concluded that use of [[pioglitazone]] is associated with a slightly higher risk of [[bladder cancer]] compared to the general population. The authors of the same analysis recommended that other blood sugar lowering agents be considered in people with other risk factors for bladder cancer such as [[cigarette smoking]], family history, or exposure to certain forms of [[chemotherapy]].<ref name=\"Ferwana2013\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Ferwana M, Firwana B, Hasan R, Al-Mallah MH, Kim S, Montori VM, Murad MH |title=Pioglitazone and risk of bladder cancer: a meta-analysis of controlled studies|journal=Diabetes Medicine|volume=30|issue=9|pages=1026\u201332|date=September 2013|pmid=23350856|doi=10.1111/dme.12144}}</ref>\n\nThiazolidinediones reduce [[bone mineral density]] and increase the risk of fractures in women, possibly as a result of biasing the differentiation of [[bone marrow stromal cells]] away from [[osteoblast]] differentiation and toward [[adipocyte]] formation.<ref name=\"Man&Dic2015\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Mannucci E, Dicembrini I |title=Drugs for type 2 diabetes: role in the regulation of bone metabolism|journal=Clin Cases Miner Bone Metab|date=May\u2013August 2015|volume=12|issue=2|pages=130\u2013134|doi=10.11138/ccmbm/2015.12.2.130|pmid=26604937|pmc=4625768}}</ref>\n\nThiazolidinediones increase expression of [[Angiotensin-converting enzyme 2|angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2)]]. It is hypothesized that this increases the chance of serious infection with the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] virus, which causes [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=\"FengKaraRoth2020\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Feng L, Karakiulakis G, Roth M|title=Are patients with hypertension and diabetes mellitus at increased risk for COVID-19 infection?|journal=The Lancet Respiratory Medicine|date=March 11, 2020|doi=10.1016/S2213-2600(20)30116-8}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Oral hypoglycemics}}\n{{PPAR modulators}}\n\n[[Category:Thiazolidinediones| ]]\n", "name_user": "78.62.97.138", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thiazolidinedione"}
{"title_page": "1966 Five Nations Championship", "text_new": "{{Infobox Six Nations Championship 2\n| name = 1966 Five Nations Championship\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| date = 15 January - 26 March 1966\n| countries = {{ru|ENG}}<br />{{ru|IRE}}<br />{{ru|FRA}}<br />{{ru|SCO}}<br />{{ru|WAL}}\n| champions =  {{ru|WAL}}\n| count = 15\n| grand slam = \n| triple crown = \n| calcutta cup = {{ru|SCO}} \n| millennium trophy = \n| centenary quaich = \n| giuseppe garibaldi trophy = \n| matches = 10\n| attendance =\n| tries = 21\n| top point scorer = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Claude Lacaze]] (14)\n| top try scorer = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Christian Darrouy]] (2)<br />{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Sandy Hinshelwood]] (2)<br />{{flagicon|SCO}} [[David Whyte (rugby union)|David Whyte]] (2)<br /> {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Ken Jones (rugby union, born 1941)|Ken Jones]] (2)\n| website = \n| previous year = 1965\n| previous tournament = 1965 Five Nations Championship\n| next year = 1967\n| next tournament = 1967 Five Nations Championship \n}}\n\nThe '''1966 Five Nations Championship''' was the thirty-seventh series of the rugby union [[Six Nations Championship|Five Nations Championship]]. Including the previous incarnations as the Home Nations and Five Nations, this was the seventy-second series of the northern hemisphere rugby union championship. Ten matches were played between 15 January and 26 March. It was contested by [[England national rugby union team|England]], [[France national rugby union team|France]], [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]], [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]] and [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]].\n\n[[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]] won their 15th title, with a single loss, while [[England national rugby union team|England]] finished in a disappointing fifth and last place.\n\n==Participants==\nThe teams involved were:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Nation'''\n!'''Venue'''\n!'''City'''\n!'''Head coach'''\n!'''Captain'''\n|-\n|{{ru|ENG}}\n|[[Twickenham Stadium|Twickenham]]\n|[[London]]\n|''none''\n|[[Budge Rogers]]\n|-\n|{{ru|FRA}}\n|[[Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir]]\n|[[Colombes]]\n|[[Jean Prat]]\n|[[Michel Crauste]]\n|-\n|{{Ru|IRE}}\n|[[Lansdowne Road]]\n|[[Dublin]]\n|''none''\n|[[Ray McLoughlin]]/[[Tom Kiernan]]\n|-\n|{{ru|SCO}}\n|[[Murrayfield Stadium|Murrayfield]]\n|[[Edinburgh]]\n|''none''\n|[[Stewart Wilson]]/[[Ian Laughland]]\n|-\n|{{ru|WAL}}\n|[[Cardiff Arms Park|National Stadium]]\n|[[Cardiff]]\n|''none''\n|[[Alun Pask]]/[[David Watkins (rugby)|David Watkins]]\n|}\n\n==Table==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2 width=\"8%\"| Position\n!rowspan=2 width=\"18%\"| Nation\n!colspan=4 width=\"32%\"| Games\n!colspan=3 width=\"32%\"| Points\n!rowspan=2 width=\"10%\"| Table<br/>points\n|-\n!width=\"8%\"| Played\n!width=\"8%\"| Won\n!width=\"8%\"| Drawn\n!width=\"8%\"| Lost\n!width=\"8%\"| For\n!width=\"8%\"| Against\n!width=\"8%\"| Difference\n|- bgcolor=#ccffcc\n|1||align=left|{{Ru|WAL}}\n|4||3||0||1||34||26||+8||'''6'''\n|-\n|2||align=left|{{Ru|FRA}}\n|4||2||1||1||35||18||+17||'''5'''\n|-\n|2||align=left|{{Ru|SCO}}\n|4||2||1||1||23||17||+6||'''5'''\n|-\n|4||align=left|{{Ru|IRE}}\n|4||1||1||2||24||34||&minus;10||'''3'''\n|-\n|5||align=left|{{Ru|ENG}}\n|4||0||1||3||15||36||&minus;21||'''1'''\n|-\n|}\n<small>(Source: rugbyfootballhistory.com:<ref>{{cite web|title=6 Nations History|url=http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/6nations.htm#3|work=Year by Year Analysis: 1966|publisher=rugbyfootballhistory.com|accessdate=20 March 2011}}</ref>)</small>\n\n==Squads==\n{{for|each nation's squad for the 1966 Five Nations Championship|1966 Five Nations Championship squads}}\n\n==Results==\n{{Rugbybox |\ndate = 1966-01-15|\nhome = {{Ru-rt|SCO}} |\nscore = 3&ndash;3 |\naway = {{Ru|FRA}} |\nhomescore = '''Tries''': [[David Whyte (rugby union)|Whyte]]|\nawayscore = '''Pen.''': [[Claude Lacaze|Lacaze]]|\nstadium = [[Murrayfield]], [[Edinburgh]] |\nattendance = 60,000 |\nreferee = D. M. Hughes (Wales)}}\n\n{{Rugbybox |\ndate = 1966-01-15|\nhome = {{Ru-rt|ENG}} |\nscore = 6&ndash;11 |\naway = {{Ru|WAL}} |\nhomescore = '''Tries''': [[David Perry (rugby union)|Perry]]<br />'''Pen.''': [[Don Rutherford|Rutherford]] |\nawayscore = '''Tries''': [[Alun Pask|Pask]]<br />'''Con.''': [[Terry Price (rugby)|Price]]<br />'''Pen.''': [[Terry Price (rugby)|Price]] (2) |\nstadium = [[Twickenham Stadium]], [[London]] |\nattendance = |\nreferee = R. W. Gilliland (Ireland)}}\n\n{{Rugbybox |\ndate = 1966-01-29|\nhome = {{Ru-rt|FRA}} |\nscore = 11&ndash;6 |\naway = {{Ru|IRE}}  |\nhomescore = '''Tries''': [[Christian Darrouy|Darrouy]] (2)<br />'''Con.''': [[Claude Lacaze|Lacaze]]<br />'''Pen.''': [[Claude Lacaze|Lacaze]] |\nawayscore = '''Pen.''': [[Mike Gibson (rugby union)|Gibson]]<br />'''Drops''': [[Tom Kiernan|Kiernan]] |\nstadium = [[Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir]], [[Colombes]] |\nattendance = 30,947 |\nreferee = P. G. Brook (England)}}\n\n{{Rugbybox |\ndate = 1966-02-05|\nhome = {{Ru-rt|WAL}} |\nscore = 8&ndash;3 |\naway = {{Ru|SCO}} |\nhomescore = '''Tries''': [[Ken Jones (rugby union, born 1941)|K. Jones]] (2)<br />'''Con.''': [[Keith Bradshaw (rugby player)|Bradshaw]] |\nawayscore = '''Pen.''': [[Stewart Wilson|Wilson]] |\nstadium = [[Cardiff Arms Park|National Stadium]], [[Cardiff]] |\nattendance = |\nreferee = M. H. Titcomb (England)}}\n\n{{Rugbybox |\ndate = 1966-02-12|\nhome = {{Ru-rt|ENG}} |\nscore = 6&ndash;6 |\naway = {{Ru|IRE}}  |\nhomescore = '''Tries''': [[Dick Greenwood|Greenwood]]<br />'''Pen.''': [[Don Rutherford|Rutherford]] |\nawayscore = '''Tries''': [[Paddy McGrath|McGrath]]<br />'''Pen.''': [[Tom Kiernan|Kiernan]] |\nstadium = [[Twickenham Stadium]], [[London]] |\nattendance = |\nreferee = R. B. L. Marie (France)}}\n\n{{Rugbybox |\ndate = 1966-02-26|\nhome = {{Ru-rt|FRA}} |\nscore = 13&ndash;0 |\naway = {{Ru|ENG}} |\nhomescore = '''Tries''': [[Andr\u00e9 Boniface|A. Boniface]]<br />[[Jean Gachassin|Gachassin]]<br />[[Arnaldo Gruarin|Gruarin]]<br />'''Con.''': [[Claude Lacaze|Lacaze]] (2)|\nawayscore =  |\nstadium = [[Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir]], [[Colombes]] |\nattendance = 37,660 |\nreferee = D. G. Walters (Wales)}}\n\n{{Rugbybox |\ndate = 1966-02-26|\nhome = {{Ru-rt|IRE}}  |\nscore = 3&ndash;11 |\naway = {{Ru|SCO}} |\nhomescore = '''Pen.''': [[Tom Kiernan|Kiernan]] |\nawayscore = '''Tries''': [[Derrick Grant|Grant]]<br />[[Sandy Hinshelwood|Hinshelwood]] (2)<br />'''Con.''': [[Stewart Wilson|Wilson]] |\nstadium = [[Lansdowne Road]], [[Dublin]] |\nattendance = |\nreferee = D. M. Hughes (Wales)}}\n\n{{Rugbybox |\ndate = 1966-03-12|\nhome = {{Ru-rt|IRE}}  |\nscore = 9&ndash;6 |\naway = {{Ru|WAL}} |\nhomescore = '''Tries''': [[Barry Bresnihan|Bresnihan]]<br />'''Pen.''': [[Mike Gibson (rugby union)|Gibson]]<br />'''Drops''': [[Mike Gibson (rugby union)|Gibson]] |\nawayscore = '''Tries''': [[Gareth Prothero|Prothero]]<br />'''Pen.''': [[Keith Bradshaw (rugby player)|Bradshaw]] |\nstadium = [[Lansdowne Road]], [[Dublin]] |\nattendance = |\nreferee = R. P. Burrell (Scotland)}}\n\n{{Rugbybox |\ndate = 1966-03-19|\nhome = {{Ru-rt|SCO}} |\nscore = 6&ndash;3 |\naway = {{Ru|ENG}} |\nhomescore = '''Tries''': [[David Whyte (rugby union)|Whyte]]<br />'''Pen.''': [[Colin Blaikie|Blaikie]] |\nawayscore = '''Drops''': [[Colin McFadyean|McFadyean]] |\nstadium = [[Murrayfield]], [[Edinburgh]] |\nattendance = |\nreferee = K. D. Kelleher (England)}}\n\n{{Rugbybox |\ndate = 1966-03-26|\nhome = {{Ru-rt|WAL}} |\nscore = 9&ndash;8 |\naway = {{Ru|FRA}} |\nhomescore = '''Tries''': [[Stuart Watkins|Watkins]]<br />'''Pen.''': [[Keith Bradshaw (rugby player)|Bradshaw]] (2)|\nawayscore = '''Tries''': [[Bernard Duprat|Duprat]]<br />[[Jean-Joseph Rupert|Rupert]]<br />'''Con.''': [[Claude Lacaze|Lacaze]] |\nstadium = [[Cardiff Arms Park|National Stadium]], [[Cardiff]] |\nattendance = 60,000 |\nreferee = K. D. Kelleher (Ireland)}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080705165434/http://www.rbs6nations.com/index_6nations.htm The official RBS Six Nations Site]\n\n{{Start box}}\n{{Succession box\n|title=[[Six Nations Championship|Five Nations Championship]]\n|before=[[1965 Five Nations Championship|1965 Five Nations]]\n|after=[[1967 Five Nations Championship|1967 Five Nations]]\n|years='''1966''' }}\n{{End box}}\n\n{{Six nations new}}\n\n[[Category:Six Nations Championship seasons]]\n[[Category:1966 rugby union tournaments for national teams|Five Nations]]\n[[Category:1966 in Irish sport|Five Nations]]\n[[Category:1965\u201366 in English rugby union|Five Nations]]\n[[Category:1965\u201366 in Welsh rugby union|Five Nations]]\n[[Category:1965\u201366 in Scottish rugby union|Five Nations]]\n[[Category:1965\u201366 in French rugby union|Five Nations]]\n[[Category:1965\u201366 in European rugby union| ]]\n[[Category:January 1966 sports events|Five Nations]]\n[[Category:February 1966 sports events|Five Nations]]\n[[Category:March 1966 sports events|Five Nations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Six Nations Championship 2\n| name = 1966 Five Nations Championship\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| date = 15 January - 26 March 1966\n| countries = {{ru|ENG}}<br />{{ru|IRE}}<br />{{ru|FRA}}<br />{{ru|SCO}}<br />{{ru|WAL}}\n| champions =  {{ru|WAL}}\n| count = 15\n| grand slam = \n| triple crown = \n| calcutta cup = {{ru|SCO}} \n| millennium trophy = \n| centenary quaich = \n| giuseppe garibaldi trophy = \n| matches = 10\n| attendance =\n| tries = 21\n| top point scorer = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Claude Lacaze]] (14)\n| top try scorer = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Christian Darrouy]] (2)<br />{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Sandy Hinshelwood]] (2)<br />{{flagicon|SCO}} [[David Whyte (rugby union)|David Whyte]] (2)<br /> {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Ken Jones (rugby union, born 1941)|Ken Jones]] (2)\n| website = \n| previous year = 1965\n| previous tournament = 1965 Five Nations Championship\n| next year = 1967\n| next tournament = 1967 Five Nations Championship \n}}\n\nThe '''1966 Five Nations Championship''' was the thirty-seventh series of the rugby union [[Six Nations Championship|Five Nations Championship]]. Including the previous incarnations as the Home Nations and Five Nations, this was the seventy-second series of the northern hemisphere rugby union championship. Ten matches were played between 15 January and 26 March. It was contested by [[England national rugby union team|England]], [[France national rugby union team|France]], [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]], [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]] and [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]].\n\n[[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]] won their 15th title, with a single loss, while [[England national rugby union team|England]] finished in a disappointing fifth and last place.\n\n==Participants==\nThe teams involved were:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Nation'''\n!'''Venue'''\n!'''City'''\n!'''Head coach'''\n!'''Captain'''\n|-\n|{{ru|ENG}}\n|[[Twickenham Stadium|Twickenham]]\n|[[London]]\n|''none''\n|[[Budge Rogers]]\n|-\n|{{ru|FRA}}\n|[[Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir]]\n|[[Colombes]]\n|[[Jean Prat]]\n|[[Michel Crauste]]\n|-\n|{{Ru|IRE}}\n|[[Lansdowne Road]]\n|[[Dublin]]\n|''none''\n|[[Ray McLoughlin]]/[[Tom Kiernan]]\n|-\n|{{ru|SCO}}\n|[[Murrayfield Stadium|Murrayfield]]\n|[[Edinburgh]]\n|''none''\n|[[Stewart Wilson]]/[[Ian Laughland]]\n|-\n|{{ru|WAL}}\n|[[Cardiff Arms Park|National Stadium]]\n|[[Cardiff]]\n|''none''\n|[[Alun Pask]]/[[David Watkins (rugby)|David Watkins]]\n|}\n\n==Table==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2 width=\"8%\"| Position\n!rowspan=2 width=\"18%\"| Nation\n!colspan=4 width=\"32%\"| Games\n!colspan=3 width=\"32%\"| Points\n!rowspan=2 width=\"10%\"| Table<br/>points\n|-\n!width=\"8%\"| Played\n!width=\"8%\"| Won\n!width=\"8%\"| Drawn\n!width=\"8%\"| Lost\n!width=\"8%\"| For\n!width=\"8%\"| Against\n!width=\"8%\"| Difference\n|- bgcolor=#ccffcc\n|1||align=left|{{Ru|WAL}}\n|4||3||0||1||34|